{"title_page": "Wrestle Peter Pan 2019", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 DDT Pro-Wrestling event}}\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name=Wrestle Peter Pan 2019\n|image=\n|caption=\n|promotion=[[DDT Pro-Wrestling]]\n|date={{dts|July 15, 2019}}<ref name=Official2019 />\n|venue=[[Ota City General Gymnasium]]<ref name=Official2019 />\n|city=[[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]<ref name=Official2019 />\n|attendance=3,798<ref name=Official2019 />\n|event=[[DDT Peter Pan|Peter Pan]]\n|lastevent2=[[Ry\u014dgoku Peter Pan 2018|2018]]\n|nextevent2=[[Wrestle Peter Pan 2020|2020]]\n}}\n\n'''Wrestle Peter Pan 2019''' was a [[professional wrestling]] event promoted by [[DDT Pro-Wrestling]] (DDT). The event took place on July 15, 2019, in [[Tokyo]] at the [[Ota City General Gymnasium]]. The event featured thirteen matches, five of which were contested for [[Championship (professional wrestling)|championships]].<ref name=Official2019>{{cite web | url = https://www.ddtpro.com/results/3312 | title=Wrestle Peter Pan 2019 | date=July 15, 2019 | accessdate=February 4, 2020 | work=[[DDT Pro-Wrestling]] | language=Japanese}}</ref><ref name=PeterPan2019CM>{{cite web | url = https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=212537 | title = DDT Ryogoku Peter Pan 2018 ~ Fall Wrestling Culture Festival ~ | accessdate = February 3, 2020 | work = Cagematch.net}}</ref> The event aired on [[Fighting TV Samurai]] and on DDT's [[video on demand]] service [[DDT Universe]].<ref name=DDT2019PL>{{cite web | url = http://www.purolove.com/misc/ddt/results/results18.php | title = DDT Pro-Wrestling Results: 2018 | language = German | accessdate = February 3, 2020 | work = Purolove.net}}</ref> This was the first Peter Pan event to have its name written in [[r\u014dmaji]].\n\n==Storylines==\nThe Wrestle Peter Pan 2019 event featured thirteen [[Professional wrestling match types|professional wrestling matches]] that involved different wrestlers from pre-existing scripted feuds and [[Narrative thread|storylines]]. Wrestlers portrayed [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villains]], [[Face (professional wrestling)|heroes]], or [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Tweener|less distinguishable characters]] in the scripted events that built tension and culminated in a wrestling match or series of matches.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/pro-wrestling.htm | title = How Pro Wrestling Works | last=Grabianowski | first=Ed | accessdate=September 13, 2014 | work=HowStuffWorks, Inc. | publisher=[[Discovery Communications]]}}</ref>\n\nBy winning the [[King of DDT Tournament#2019|King of DDT]] tournament on May 19, [[Konosuke Takeshita]] earned a title match in the main event against [[KO-D Openweight Championship|KO-D Openweight Champion]] [[Tetsuya Endo (wrestler)|Tetsuya Endo]].\n\n==Event==\nFirst on the undercard was an exhibition match presented by Hotel Cent Inn Kurashiki between trainee Keigo Nakamura and Kota Umeda.\n\nNext was a [[Six-man tag team match|six-woman tag team match]] presented by JPA, an accounting management company, featuring [[Tokyo Joshi Pro Wrestling]] talents.\n\nOn the main card, Saki Akai faced [[Yoshiko (wrestler)|Yoshiko]] from [[Seadlinnng|SEAdLINNNG]].\n\nNext, Akito defended the [[DDT Extreme Division Championship]] against Asuka in an [[Hardcore wrestling|Ippon Fluorescent Light Tube Deathmatch]] in which a single light tube was used. Per the rules, whoever would break the tube would be declared the loser of the match.\n\nBefore the next match, a backstage segment was shown in which [[Toru Owashi]], the then [[Ironman Heavymetalweight Championship|Ironman Heavymetalweight Champion]], broke up an argument between Gorgeous Matsuno and masked wrestler Furitsuke Kamen. Matsuno and Furitsuke began fighting until Furitsuke was unmasked, revealing that he was actually Lucky Ikeda, a well-known ''[[tarento]]''. In the confusion, Ikeda [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pinned]] Owashi to become the 1,375th champion.\n\nDuring the [[Professional wrestling match types#Rumble rules battle royals|Rumble rules match]], the title went from Ikeda to Matsuno to Tomomitsu Matsunaga to [[Masato Shibata|Mad Paulie]] and then to Kazuki Hirata before Hirata was eventually eliminated by [[Yukio Sakaguchi]]. Michiaki Nakano from Souken Holdings, a sponsor of the match, presented Sakaguchi with the match prize then tried to pin him but Sakaguchi stopped him.\n\nNext was a match dubbed \"2nd Generation Human Windmill vs. 3rd Generation Taih\u014d\" between [[Hideki Suzuki]] (whose nickname is \"The 2nd Generation Human Windmill\") and Yukio Naya (the grandson of [[Taih\u014d K\u014dki]], the 48th [[Yokozuna (sumo)|yokozuna]] in the sport of [[sumo wrestling]]).\n\n[[Sanshiro Takagi]] faced Super Sasadango Machine in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Weapon-based variations|Weapon Rumble match]] in which various weapons secretly chosen by the participants beforehand were being introduced one after another at regular intervals. This was a title match for the inaugural [[O-40 Championship]], a title reserved for wrestlers over 40 years old.\n\nNext, [[mixed martial artist]] [[Shinya Aoki]] faced [[Danshoku Dino]] in a match with special rules. The match was limited to ten rounds lasting three minutes each, every odd numbered round would be fought under strict fighting rules with no pins allowed and every even numbered round would be fought under regular professional wrestling rules with \"courtship\" allowed. Mina Shirakawa was the [[ring girl]] for the odd numbered rounds and Yuki Iino was the \"ring boy\" for the even numbered rounds.\n\nNext, Damnation ([[Daisuke Sasaki]] and Soma Takao) defended the [[KO-D Tag Team Championship]] against the team of [[Harashima]] and Yasu Urano in a match sponsored by Souken Holdings.\n\nIn the main event, [[Konosuke Takeshita]] challenged [[Tetsuya Endo (wrestler)|Tetsuya Endo]] for the [[KO-D Openweight Championship]]. Takeshita won the bout and was granted a 2,000,000 [[Japanese yen|yen]] prize and one year of Blackout products by Casting Dot JP Co., Ltd., the sponsor of the match.\n\n==Results==\n{{Professional wrestling results table\n|future  = no\n|results = <ref name=Official2019 /><ref name=PeterPan2019CM /><ref name=DDT2019PL />\n|match1  = Kota Umeda defeated Keigo Nakamura\n|stip1   = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time1   = 5:07\n|pre1    = yes\n\n|match2  = Rika Tatsumi and The Bakuretsu Sisters (Nodoka Tenma and Yuki Aino) defeated Natsumi Maki, Yuna Manase and Himawari Unagi\n|stip2   = [[Six-man tag team match|Six-woman tag team match]]\n|time2   = 10:35\n|pre2    = yes\n\n|match3  = All Out (Shunma Katsumata and Yuki Iino) and Mizuki Watase defeated Disaster Box (Yuki Ueno and Naomi Yoshimura) and Nobuhiro Shimatani\n|stip3   = [[Six-man tag team match]]\n|time3   = 12:11\n\n|match4  = Kazusada Higuchi and Ryota Nakatsu defeated Kota Umeda and Kouki Iwasaki\n|stip4   = [[Tag team match]]\n|time4   = 13:26\n\n|match5  = [[Yoshiko (wrestler)|Yoshiko]] defeated Saki Akai\n|stip5   = Singles match\n|time5   = 8:32\n\n|match6  = Akito (c) defeated Asuka by ippon{{efn|In this context, a [[Fluorescent lamp|light tube]] breakage.}}\n|stip6   = [[Hardcore wrestling|Ippon Fluorescent Light Tube Deathmatch]] for the [[DDT Extreme Division Championship]]\n|time6   = 11:48\n\n|match7  = [[Yukio Sakaguchi]] won by last eliminating Kazuki Hirata\n|stip7   = [[Professional wrestling match types#Rumble rules battle royals|Rumble rules match]] for the [[Ironman Heavymetalweight Championship]]\n|time7   = 20:04\n\n|match8  = [[Hideki Suzuki]] defeated Yukio Naya\n|stip8   = Singles match\n|time8   = 7:59\n\n|match9  = Chris Brookes and [[Masahiro Takanashi]] defeated Moonlight Express (Mao and Mike Bailey)\n|stip9   = Tag team match\n|time9   = 11:24\n\n|match10  = [[Sanshiro Takagi]] defeated Super Sasadango Machine\n|stip10   = [[Professional wrestling match types#Weapon-based variations|Weapon Rumble]] for the inaugural [[O-40 Championship]]\n|time10   = 28:56\n\n|match11  = [[Shinya Aoki]] defeated [[Danshoku Dino]] by [[technical submission]]\n|stip11   = Special rules match\n|time11   = 4R 2:54\n\n|match12  = Damnation ([[Daisuke Sasaki]] and Soma Takao) (c) defeated UraShima ([[Harashima]] and Yasu Urano)\n|stip12   = Tag team match for the [[KO-D Tag Team Championship]]\n|time12   = 24:21\n\n|match13  = [[Konosuke Takeshita]] defeated [[Tetsuya Endo (wrestler)|Tetsuya Endo]] (c) by [[Submission (professional wrestling)|submission]]\n|stip13   = Singles match for the [[KO-D Openweight Championship]]\n|time13   = 31:38\n}}\n\n===Rumble rules match===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Order<ref name=Rumble>{{cite web | url = https://dramaticddt.wordpress.com/past-results/ddt-results-2019/ | title=DDT Results 2019 | accessdate=February 4, 2020 | work=Dramatic DDT}}</ref>\n! Wrestler\n! Order eliminated\n! By\n! Time\n|-\n| {{sort|01|1}} || {{sort|Ikeda|Lucky Ikeda}} (c) || {{sort|01|1}} || Gorgeous Matsuno{{efn|Matsuno becomes the 1,376th champion.}} || 3:37\n|-\n| {{sort|02|2}} || {{sort|Matsuno|Gorgeous Matsuno}} || {{sort|02|2}} || Tomomitsu Matsunaga{{efn|Matsunaga becomes the 1,377th champion.}} || 3:48\n|-\n| {{sort|03|3}} || {{sort|Matsunaga|Tomomitsu Matsunaga}} || {{sort|03|3}} || Mad Paulie{{efn|Paulie becomes the 1,378th champion.}} || 5:40\n|-\n| {{sort|04|4}} || {{sort|Pokotan|Pokotan}} || {{sort|07|7}} || Shiro Koshinaka || 14:09\n|-\n| {{sort|05|5}} || {{sortname|Makoto|Oishi}} || {{sort|08|8}} || Shiro Koshinaka || 18:34\n|-\n| {{sort|06|6}} || {{sort|Hirata|Kazuki Hirata}} || {{sort|14|14}} || Yukio Sakaguchi || 20:04\n|-\n| {{sort|07|7}} || {{sortname|Mad|Paulie|Masato Shibata}} || {{sort|04|4}} || Kazuki Hirata{{efn|Hirata becomes the 1,379th champion.}} || 7:49\n|-\n| {{sort|08|8}} || {{sort|Kamifuku|Yuki Kamifuku}} || {{sort|06|6}} || Joey Ryan || 11:43\n|-\n| {{sort|09|9}} || {{sortname||Kuro-chan|Kuro chan (Comedian)}} || {{sort|05|5}} || Yuki Kamifuku || 11:30\n|-style=\"background:gold\"\n| '''{{sort|10|10}}''' || '''{{sortname|Yukio|Sakaguchi}}''' || {{sort|15|&mdash;}} || &mdash; || '''Winner'''\n|-\n| {{sort|11|11}} || {{sortname|Joey|Ryan|dab=wrestler}} || {{sort|09|9}} || Shiro Koshinaka || 18:34\n|-\n| {{sort|12|12}} || {{sortname|Hiroshi|Yamato}} || {{sort|10|10}} || Shiro Koshinaka || 18:34\n|-\n| {{sort|13|13}} || {{sortname|Toru|Owashi}} || {{sort|13|13}} || Kazuki Hirata || 19:08\n|-\n| {{sort|14|14}} || {{sortname|Shiro|Koshinaka}} || {{sort|12|12}} || Kazuki Hirata || 19:08\n|-\n| {{sort|15|15}} || {{sort|Honda|Antonio Honda}} || {{sort|11|11}} || Kazuki Hirata || 19:08\n|}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ddtpro.com/ The official DDT Pro-Wrestling website]\n*[http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/lucha/ddt/peterpan.html#2019 Wrestle Peter Pan 2019 at ProWrestlingHistory.com]\n\n{{Professional wrestling in Japan}}\n\n[[Category:DDT Peter Pan]]\n[[Category:2019 in professional wrestling]]\n[[Category:July 2019 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:2019 in Japan]]\n[[Category:Events in Tokyo]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 DDT Pro-Wrestling event}}\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name=Wrestle Peter Pan 2019\n|image=\n|caption=\n|promotion=[[DDT Pro-Wrestling]]\n|date={{dts|July 15, 2019}}<ref name=Official2019 />\n|venue=[[Ota City General Gymnasium]]<ref name=Official2019 />\n|city=[[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]<ref name=Official2019 />\n|attendance=3,798<ref name=Official2019 />\n|event=[[DDT Peter Pan|Peter Pan]]\n|lastevent2=[[Ry\u014dgoku Peter Pan 2018|2018]]\n|nextevent2=[[Wrestle Peter Pan 2020|2020]]\n}}\n\n'''Wrestle Peter Pan 2019''' was a [[professional wrestling]] event promoted by [[DDT Pro-Wrestling]] (DDT). The event took place on July 15, 2019, in [[Tokyo]] at the [[Ota City General Gymnasium]]. The event featured thirteen matches, five of which were contested for [[Championship (professional wrestling)|championships]].<ref name=Official2019>{{cite web | url = https://www.ddtpro.com/results/3312 | title=Wrestle Peter Pan 2019 | date=July 15, 2019 | accessdate=February 4, 2020 | work=[[DDT Pro-Wrestling]] | language=Japanese}}</ref><ref name=PeterPan2019CM>{{cite web | url = https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=212537 | title = DDT Ryogoku Peter Pan 2018 ~ Fall Wrestling Culture Festival ~ | accessdate = February 3, 2020 | work = Cagematch.net}}</ref> The event aired on [[Fighting TV Samurai]] and on DDT's [[video on demand]] service [[DDT Universe]].<ref name=DDT2019PL>{{cite web | url = http://www.purolove.com/misc/ddt/results/results18.php | title = DDT Pro-Wrestling Results: 2018 | language = German | accessdate = February 3, 2020 | work = Purolove.net}}</ref> This was the first Peter Pan event to have its name written in [[r\u014dmaji]].\n\n==Storylines==\nThe Wrestle Peter Pan 2019 event featured thirteen [[Professional wrestling match types|professional wrestling matches]] that involved different wrestlers from pre-existing scripted feuds and [[Narrative thread|storylines]]. Wrestlers portrayed [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villains]], [[Face (professional wrestling)|heroes]], or [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Tweener|less distinguishable characters]] in the scripted events that built tension and culminated in a wrestling match or series of matches.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/pro-wrestling.htm | title = How Pro Wrestling Works | last=Grabianowski | first=Ed | accessdate=September 13, 2014 | work=HowStuffWorks, Inc. | publisher=[[Discovery Communications]]}}</ref>\n\nBy winning the [[King of DDT Tournament#2019|King of DDT]] tournament on May 19, [[Konosuke Takeshita]] earned a title match in the main event against [[KO-D Openweight Championship|KO-D Openweight Champion]] [[Tetsuya Endo (wrestler)|Tetsuya Endo]].\n\n==Event==\nFirst on the undercard was an exhibition match presented by Hotel Cent Inn Kurashiki between trainee Keigo Nakamura and Kota Umeda.\n\nNext was a [[Six-man tag team match|six-woman tag team match]] presented by JPA, an accounting management company, featuring [[Tokyo Joshi Pro Wrestling]] talents.\n\nOn the main card, Saki Akai faced [[Yoshiko (wrestler)|Yoshiko]] from [[Seadlinnng|SEAdLINNNG]].\n\nNext, Akito defended the [[DDT Extreme Division Championship]] against Asuka in an [[Hardcore wrestling|Ippon Fluorescent Light Tube Deathmatch]] in which a single light tube was used. Per the rules, whoever would break the tube would be declared the loser of the match.\n\nBefore the next match, a backstage segment was shown in which [[Toru Owashi]], the then [[Ironman Heavymetalweight Championship|Ironman Heavymetalweight Champion]], broke up an argument between Gorgeous Matsuno and masked wrestler Furitsuke Kamen. Matsuno and Furitsuke began fighting until Furitsuke was unmasked, revealing that he was actually Lucky Ikeda, a well-known ''[[tarento]]''. In the confusion, Ikeda [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pinned]] Owashi to become the 1,375th champion.\n\nDuring the [[Professional wrestling match types#Rumble rules battle royals|Rumble rules match]], the title went from Ikeda to Matsuno to Tomomitsu Matsunaga to [[Masato Shibata|Mad Paulie]] and then to Kazuki Hirata before Hirata was eventually eliminated by [[Yukio Sakaguchi]]. Michiaki Nakano from Souken Holdings, a sponsor of the match, presented Sakaguchi with the match prize then tried to pin him but Sakaguchi stopped him.\n\nNext was a match dubbed \"2nd Generation Human Windmill vs. 3rd Generation Taih\u014d\" between [[Hideki Suzuki]] (whose nickname is \"The 2nd Generation Human Windmill\") and Yukio Naya (the grandson of [[Taih\u014d K\u014dki]], the 48th [[Yokozuna (sumo)|yokozuna]] in the sport of [[sumo wrestling]]).\n\n[[Sanshiro Takagi]] faced Super Sasadango Machine in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Weapon-based variations|Weapon Rumble match]] in which various weapons secretly chosen by the participants beforehand were being introduced one after an other at regular intervals. This was a title match for the inaugural [[O-40 Championship]], a title reserved for wrestlers over 40 years old.\n\nNext, [[mixed martial artist]] [[Shinya Aoki]] faced [[Danshoku Dino]] in a match with special rules. The match was limited to ten rounds lasting three minutes each, every odd numbered round would be fought under strict fighting rules with no pins allowed and every even numbered round would be fought under regular professional wrestling rules with \"courtship\" allowed. Mina Shirakawa was the [[ring girl]] for the odd numbered rounds and Yuki Iino was the \"ring boy\" for the even numbered rounds.\n\nNext, Damnation ([[Daisuke Sasaki]] and Soma Takao) defended the [[KO-D Tag Team Championship]] against the team of [[Harashima]] and Yasu Urano in a match sponsored by Souken Holdings.\n\nIn the main event, [[Konosuke Takeshita]] challenged [[Tetsuya Endo (wrestler)|Tetsuya Endo]] for the [[KO-D Openweight Championship]]. Takeshita won the bout and was granted a 2,000,000 [[Japanese yen|yen]] prize and one year of Blackout products by Casting Dot JP Co., Ltd., the sponsor of the match.\n\n==Results==\n{{Professional wrestling results table\n|future  = no\n|results = <ref name=Official2019 /><ref name=PeterPan2019CM /><ref name=DDT2019PL />\n|match1  = Kota Umeda defeated Keigo Nakamura\n|stip1   = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time1   = 5:07\n|pre1    = yes\n\n|match2  = Rika Tatsumi and The Bakuretsu Sisters (Nodoka Tenma and Yuki Aino) defeated Natsumi Maki, Yuna Manase and Himawari Unagi\n|stip2   = [[Six-man tag team match|Six-woman tag team match]]\n|time2   = 10:35\n|pre2    = yes\n\n|match3  = All Out (Shunma Katsumata and Yuki Iino) and Mizuki Watase defeated Disaster Box (Yuki Ueno and Naomi Yoshimura) and Nobuhiro Shimatani\n|stip3   = [[Six-man tag team match]]\n|time3   = 12:11\n\n|match4 