amatic DDT}}</ref>\n! Wrestler\n! Order eliminated\n! By\n! Time\n|-\n| {{sort|01|1}} || {{sort|Ikeda|Lucky Ikeda}} (c) || {{sort|01|1}} || Gorgeous Matsuno{{efn|Matsuno becomes the 1,376th champion.}} || 3:37\n|-\n| {{sort|02|2}} || {{sort|Matsuno|Gorgeous Matsuno}} || {{sort|02|2}} || Tomomitsu Matsunaga{{efn|Matsunaga becomes the 1,377th champion.}} || 3:48\n|-\n| {{sort|03|3}} || {{sort|Matsunaga|Tomomitsu Matsunaga}} || {{sort|03|3}} || Mad Paulie{{efn|Paulie becomes the 1,378th champion.}} || 5:40\n|-\n| {{sort|04|4}} || {{sort|Pokotan|Pokotan}} || {{sort|07|7}} || Shiro Koshinaka || 14:09\n|-\n| {{sort|05|5}} || {{sortname|Makoto|Oishi}} || {{sort|08|8}} || Shiro Koshinaka || 18:34\n|-\n| {{sort|06|6}} || {{sort|Hirata|Kazuki Hirata}} || {{sort|14|14}} || Yukio Sakaguchi || 20:04\n|-\n| {{sort|07|7}} || {{sortname|Mad|Paulie|Masato Shibata}} || {{sort|04|4}} || Kazuki Hirata{{efn|Hirata becomes the 1,379th champion.}} || 7:49\n|-\n| {{sort|08|8}} || {{sort|Kamifuku|Yuki Kamifuku}} || {{sort|06|6}} || Joey Ryan || 11:43\n|-\n| {{sort|09|9}} || {{sortname||Kuro-chan|Kuro chan (Comedian)}} || {{sort|05|5}} || Yuki Kamifuku || 11:30\n|-style=\"background:gold\"\n| '''{{sort|10|10}}''' || '''{{sortname|Yukio|Sakaguchi}}''' || {{sort|15|&mdash;}} || &mdash; || '''Winner'''\n|-\n| {{sort|11|11}} || {{sortname|Joey|Ryan|dab=wrestler}} || {{sort|09|9}} || Shiro Koshinaka || 18:34\n|-\n| {{sort|12|12}} || {{sortname|Hiroshi|Yamato}} || {{sort|10|10}} || Shiro Koshinaka || 18:34\n|-\n| {{sort|13|13}} || {{sortname|Toru|Owashi}} || {{sort|13|13}} || Kazuki Hirata || 19:08\n|-\n| {{sort|14|14}} || {{sortname|Shiro|Koshinaka}} || {{sort|12|12}} || Kazuki Hirata || 19:08\n|-\n| {{sort|15|15}} || {{sort|Honda|Antonio Honda}} || {{sort|11|11}} || Kazuki Hirata || 19:08\n|}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ddtpro.com/ The official DDT Pro-Wrestling website]\n*[http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/lucha/ddt/peterpan.html#2019 Wrestle Peter Pan 2019 at ProWrestlingHistory.com]\n\n{{Professional wrestling in Japan}}\n\n[[Category:DDT Peter Pan]]\n[[Category:2019 in professional wrestling]]\n[[Category:July 2019 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:2019 in Japan]]\n[[Category:Events in Tokyo]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEvent:Typo fixing, replaced: an other  \u2192  another", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wrestle_Peter_Pan_2019"}
{"title_page": "Plutonium hexafluoride", "text_new": "{{Expand German|Plutonium(VI)-fluorid|date=November 2012}}\n{{Chembox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 404346614\n| Name = \n| Reference = <ref name=\"hand\">{{cite book|last = Lide|first = David R.|year = 2009|title = Handbook of Chemistry and Physics|edition = 90|location = Boca Raton, Florida|publisher = CRC Press|isbn = 978-1-4200-9084-0|pages = 4\u201381}} ([https://www.webelements.com/compounds/plutonium/plutonium_hexafluoride.html webelements.com])</ref>\n| ImageFile = Plutonium hexafluoride.svg\n| ImageFile1 = Neptunium(VI)-fluoride-3D-vdW.png\n| ImageFile_Ref = {{Chemboximage|correct|??}}\n| ImageSize = 121\n| ImageName = Stereo structural formula of plutonium hexafluoride\n| OtherNames = \n| IUPACName = plutonium(VI) fluoride\n| SystematicName = <!-- Hexafluoroplutonium (substitutive) OR Hexafluoridoplutonium (additive) -->\n| Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| CASNo = 13693-06-6\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| PubChem = 518809\n| ChemSpiderID = 452599\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|changed|chemspider}}\n| SMILES = F[Pu](F)(F)(F)(F)F\n| StdInChI = 1S/6FH.Pu/h6*1H;/q;;;;;;+6/p-6\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = OJSBUHMRXCPOJV-UHFFFAOYSA-H\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n}}\n| Section2 = {{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = {{Chem|Pu|F|6}} \n| Appearance = Dark red, opaque crystals\n| Density = 5.08 g\u00b7cm<sup>\u22123</sup>\n| MeltingPtC = 52\n| BoilingPtC = 62\n}}\n| Section3 = {{Chembox Structure\n| CrystalStruct = [[Orthorhombic]], [[Pearson symbol|oP28]]\n| SpaceGroup = Pnma, No. 62\n| Coordination = octahedral (''O<sub>h</sub>'')\n| Dipole = 0 D\n}}\n| Section4 = {{Chembox Related\n| OtherFunction_label = fluoroplutoniums\n| OtherFunction = [[Plutonium trifluoride]]<br />\n[[Plutonium tetrafluoride]]\n}}\n| Section5 = {{Chembox Hazards\n| EUClass = '''[[Radiation]] hazard'''<br>{{Hazchem T+}}{{Hazchem C}}{{Hazchem O}}{{Hazchem N}} \n| NFPA-H = 4 \n| NFPA-F = 0\n| NFPA-R = 4\n| NFPA-S = RA\n}}\n| Section6 = \n}} \n'''Plutonium hexafluoride''' is the highest fluoride of [[plutonium]], and is of interest for [[AVLIS|laser enrichment]] of plutonium, in particular for the production of pure [[plutonium-239]] from irradiated uranium.  This pure plutonium is needed to avoid premature ignition of low-mass [[nuclear weapon]] designs by neutrons produced by spontaneous fission of [[plutonium-240]].\n\nIt is a red-brown volatile crystalline solid;<ref name=\"hand\"/> the heat of sublimation is 12.1 kcal/mol<ref name=\"JINC_1956_368\">{{cite journal |journal=[[Journal of Inorganic and Nuclear Chemistry]] |doi=10.1016/0022-1902(56)80091-2 |title=Preparation and properties of plutonium hexafluoride and identification of plutonium(VI) oxyfluoride |first=Alan E. |last=Florin |first2=Irving R. |last2=Tannenbaum |first3=Joe F. |last3=Lemons |volume=2 |issue=5\u20136 |page=368\u2013379 |year=1956 }}</ref> and the heat of vaporization 7.4 kcal/mol.<ref name=\"JINC_1956_368\"/>  It is relatively hard to handle, being very corrosive and prone to auto-[[radiolysis]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=Ned E. |last=Bibler |title=&alpha; and &beta; Radiolysis of Plutonium Hexafluoride Vapor |journal=[[J. Phys. Chem.]] |doi=10.1021/j100480a001 |date=August 23, 1979 |volume=83 |number=17 |page=2179\u20132186 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[Journal of Inorganic and Nuclear Chemistry]] |doi=10.1016/0022-1902(64)80011-7 |title=The decomposition of plutonium hexafluoride by gamma radiation |first=M.J. |last=Steindler |first2=D.V. |last2=Steidl |first3=J. |last3=Fischer |volume=26 |issue=11 |date=November 1964 |page=1869\u20131878 }}</ref>\n\nIt is prepared by fluorination of [[plutonium tetrafluoride]] (PuF<sub>4</sub>) by powerful fluorinating agents such as elemental fluorine.<ref name=\"JINC_1956_368\"/><ref>{{cite web | author= A. E. Florin | url = http://www.fas.org/sgp/othergov/doe/lanl/lib-www/la-pubs/00419717.pdf | title = Plutonium Hexafluoride: Second Report On The Preparation and Properties (LA-1168) | publisher = Los Alamos Scientific Laboratory | date= 9 November 1950}}</ref><ref name=\"JINC_1956_358\">{{cite journal |journal=[[Journal of Inorganic and Nuclear Chemistry]] |doi=10.1016/0022-1902(56)80090-0 |title=Plutonium hexafluoride |first=C.J. |last=Mandleberg |first2=H.K. |last2=Rae |first3=R. |last3=Hurst |first4=G. |last4=Long |first5=D. |last5=Davies |first6=K.E. |last6=Francis |volume=2 |issue=5\u20136 |page=358\u2013367 |year=1956 }}</ref><ref name=\"JINC_1956_380\">{{cite journal |journal=[[Journal of Inorganic and Nuclear Chemistry]] |volume=2 |issue=5\u20136 |doi=10.1016/0022-1902(56)80092-4 |title=The properties of plutonium hexafluoride |first=Bernard |last=Weinstock |first2=John G. |last2=Malm |date=July 1956 |page=380\u2013394 }}</ref>\n\n:{{chem|Pu|F|4}} + {{chem|F|2}} \u2192 {{chem|Pu|F|6}}\n\nIt can also be obtained by fluorination of [[plutonium(III) fluoride]] or [[plutonium(IV) oxide]].<ref name=\"JINC_1956_358\"/>\n\n:2 {{chem|Pu|F|3}} + 3 {{chem|F|2}} \u2192 2 {{chem|Pu|F|6}}\n\n:{{chem|Pu|O|2}} + 3 {{chem|F|2}} \u2192 {{chem|Pu|F|6}} + {{chem|O|2}}\n\nIn 1984, the synthesis of plutonium hexafluoride was achieved at unprecedented low temperatures through the use of [[dioxygen difluoride]]. Previous techniques needed temperatures so high that the plutonium hexafluoride produced would decompose rapidly.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Malm | first1 = J. G. | last2 = Eller | first2 = P. G. | last3 = Asprey | first3 = L. B. | year = 1984 | title = Low temperature synthesis of plutonium hexafluoride using dioxygen difluoride | url = | journal = [[Journal of the American Chemical Society]] | volume = 106 | issue = 9| pages = 2726\u20132727 | doi=10.1021/ja00321a056}}</ref> [[Hydrogen fluoride]] is not sufficient;<ref>{{cite book |doi=10.17226/5538 |url=https://www.nap.edu/read/5538/chapter/5#42 |page=42 |title=Evaluation of the U.S. Department of Energy's Alternatives for the Removal and Disposition of Molten Salt Reactor Experiment Fluoride Salts |year=1997 |isbn=978-0-309-05684-7 }}</ref> even though it is a powerful fluorinating agent.\n\nUnder laser irradiation at a wavelength of less than 520&nbsp;nm, it decomposes to [[plutonium pentafluoride]] and [[fluorine]];<ref>{{cite patent |country=US |number=4670239 |status= |title=Photochemical Preparation of Plutonium Pentafluoride |pubdate=June 2, 1987 |fdate=December 20, 1977 |invent1=Sherman W. Rabideau |invent2=George M. Campbell |assign1=The United States of America |url=http://www.freepatentsonline.com/4670239.html}}</ref> after more irradiation it decomposes further to [[plutonium tetrafluoride]].<ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[Journal of Fluorine Chemistry]] |doi=10.1016/S0022-1139(00)80734-4 |first=E. A. |last=Lobikov |first2=V. N. |last2=Prusakov |first3=V. F. |last3=Serik |title=Plutonium Hexafluoride Decomposition under the Action of Laser Radiation |date=August-September 1992 |volume=58 |issue=2\u20133 |page=277 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Hexafluorides}}\n{{Plutonium compounds}}\n{{fluorine compounds}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n\n[[Category:Plutonium compounds]]\n[[Category:Hexafluorides]]\n[[Category:Octahedral compounds]]\n[[Category:Metal halides]]\n[[Category:Nuclear materials]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand German|Plutonium(VI)-fluorid|date=November 2012}}\n{{Chembox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 404346614\n| Name = \n| Reference = <ref name=\"hand\">{{cite book|last = Lide|first = David R.|year = 2009|title = Handbook of Chemistry and Physics|edition = 90|location = Boca Raton, Florida|publisher = CRC Press|isbn = 978-1-4200-9084-0|pages = 4\u201381}} ([https://www.webelements.com/compounds/plutonium/plutonium_hexafluoride.html webelements.com])</ref>\n| ImageFile = Plutonium hexafluoride.svg\n| ImageFile1 = Neptunium(VI)-fluoride-3D-SF.png\n| ImageFile_Ref = {{Chemboximage|correct|??}}\n| ImageSize = 121\n| ImageName = Stereo structural formula of plutonium hexafluoride\n| OtherNames = \n| IUPACName = plutonium(VI) fluoride\n| SystematicName = <!-- Hexafluoroplutonium (substitutive) OR Hexafluoridoplutonium (additive) -->\n| Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| CASNo = 13693-06-6\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| PubChem = 518809\n| ChemSpiderID = 452599\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|changed|chemspider}}\n| SMILES = F[Pu](F)(F)(F)(F)F\n| StdInChI = 1S/6FH.Pu/h6*1H;/q;;;;;;+6/p-6\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = OJSBUHMRXCPOJV-UHFFFAOYSA-H\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n}}\n| Section2 = {{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = {{Chem|Pu|F|6}} \n| Appearance = Dark red, opaque crystals\n| Density = 5.08 g\u00b7cm<sup>\u22123</sup>\n| MeltingPtC = 52\n| BoilingPtC = 62\n}}\n| Section3 = {{Chembox Structure\n| CrystalStruct = [[Orthorhombic]], [[Pearson symbol|oP28]]\n| SpaceGroup = Pnma, No. 62\n| Coordination = octahedral (''O<sub>h</sub>'')\n| Dipole = 0 D\n}}\n| Section4 = {{Chembox Related\n| OtherFunction_label = fluoroplutoniums\n| OtherFunction = [[Plutonium trifluoride]]<br />\n[[Plutonium tetrafluoride]]\n}}\n| Section5 = {{Chembox Hazards\n| EUClass = '''[[Radiation]] hazard'''<br>{{Hazchem T+}}{{Hazchem C}}{{Hazchem O}}{{Hazchem N}} \n| NFPA-H = 4 \n| NFPA-F = 0\n| NFPA-R = 4\n| NFPA-S = RA\n}}\n| Section6 = \n}} \n'''Plutonium hexafluoride''' is the highest fluoride of [[plutonium]], and is of interest for [[AVLIS|laser enrichment]] of plutonium, in particular for the production of pure [[plutonium-239]] from irradiated uranium.  This pure plutonium is needed to avoid premature ignition of low-mass [[nuclear weapon]] designs by neutrons produced by spontaneous fission of [[plutonium-240]].\n\nIt is a red-brown volatile crystalline solid;<ref name=\"hand\"/> the heat of sublimation is 12.1 kcal/mol<ref name=\"JINC_1956_368\">{{cite journal |journal=[[Journal of Inorganic and Nuclear Chemistry]] |doi=10.1016/0022-1902(56)80091-2 |title=Preparation and properties of plutonium hexafluoride and identification of plutonium(VI) oxyfluoride |first=Alan E. |last=Florin |first2=Irving R. |last2=Tannenbaum |first3=Joe F. |last3=Lemons |volume=2 |issue=5\u20136 |page=368\u2013379 |year=1956 }}</ref> and the heat of vaporization 7.4 kcal/mol.<ref name=\"JINC_1956_368\"/>  It is relatively hard to handle, being very corrosive and prone to auto-[[radiolysis]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=Ned E. |last=Bibler |title=&alpha; and &beta; Radiolysis of Plutonium Hexafluoride Vapor |journal=[[J. Phys. Chem.]] |doi=10.1021/j100480a001 |date=August 23, 1979 |volume=83 |number=17 |page=2179\u20132186 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[Journal of Inorganic and Nuclear Chemistry]] |doi=10.1016/0022-1902(64)80011-7 |title=The decomposition of plutonium hexafluoride by gamma radiation |first=M.J. |last=Steindler |first2=D.V. |last2=Steidl |first3=J. |last3=Fischer |volume=26 |issue=11 |date=November 1964 |page=1869\u20131878 }}</ref>\n\nIt is prepared by fluorination of [[plutonium tetrafluoride]] (PuF<sub>4</sub>) by powerful fluorinating agents such as elemental fluorine.<ref name=\"JINC_1956_368\"/><ref>{{cite web | author= A. E. Florin | url = http://www.fas.org/sgp/othergov/doe/lanl/lib-www/la-pubs/00419717.pdf | title = Plutonium Hexafluoride: Second Report On The Preparation and Properties (LA-1168) | publisher = Los Alamos Scientific Laboratory | date= 9 November 1950}}</ref><ref name=\"JINC_1956_358\">{{cite journal |journal=[[Journal of Inorganic and Nuclear Chemistry]] |doi=10.1016/0022-1902(56)80090-0 |title=Plutonium hexafluoride |first=C.J. |last=Mandleberg |first2=H.K. |last2=Rae |first3=R. |last3=Hurst |first4=G. |last4=Long |first5=D. |last5=Davies |first6=K.E. |last6=Francis |volume=2 |issue=5\u20136 |page=358\u2013367 |year=1956 }}</ref><ref name=\"JINC_1956_380\">{{cite journal |journal=[[Journal of Inorganic and Nuclear Chemistry]] |volume=2 |issue=5\u20136 |doi=10.1016/0022-1902(56)80092-4 |title=The properties of plutonium hexafluoride |first=Bernard |last=Weinstock |first2=John G. |last2=Malm |date=July 1956 |page=380\u2013394 }}</ref>\n\n:{{chem|Pu|F|4}} + {{chem|F|2}} \u2192 {{chem|Pu|F|6}}\n\nIt can also be obtained by fluorination of [[plutonium(III) fluoride]] or [[plutonium(IV) oxide]].<ref name=\"JINC_1956_358\"/>\n\n:2 {{chem|Pu|F|3}} + 3 {{chem|F|2}} \u2192 2 {{chem|Pu|F|6}}\n\n:{{chem|Pu|O|2}} + 3 {{chem|F|2}} \u2192 {{chem|Pu|F|6}} + {{chem|O|2}}\n\nIn 1984, the synthesis of plutonium hexafluoride was achieved at unprecedented low temperatures through the use of [[dioxygen difluoride]]. Previous techniques needed temperatures so high that the plutonium hexafluoride produced would decompose rapidly.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Malm | first1 = J. G. | last2 = Eller | first2 = P. G. | last3 = Asprey | first3 = L. B. | year = 1984 | title = Low temperature synthesis of plutonium hexafluoride using dioxygen difluoride | url = | journal = [[Journal of the American Chemical Society]] | volume = 106 | issue = 9| pages = 2726\u20132727 | doi=10.1021/ja00321a056}}</ref> [[Hydrogen fluoride]] is not sufficient;<ref>{{cite book |doi=10.17226/5538 |url=https://www.nap.edu/read/5538/chapter/5#42 |page=42 |title=Evaluation of the U.S. Department of Energy's Alternatives for the Removal and Disposition of Molten Salt Reactor Experiment Fluoride Salts |year=1997 |isbn=978-0-309-05684-7 }}</ref> even though it is a powerful fluorinating agent.\n\nUnder laser irradiation at a wavelength of less than 520&nbsp;nm, it decomposes to [[plutonium pentafluoride]] and [[fluorine]];<ref>{{cite patent |country=US |number=4670239 |status= |title=Photochemical Preparation of Plutonium Pentafluoride |pubdate=June 2, 1987 |fdate=December 20, 1977 |invent1=Sherman W. Rabideau |invent2=George M. Campbell |assign1=The United States of America |url=http://www.freepatentsonline.com/4670239.html}}</ref> after more irradiation it decomposes further to [[plutonium tetrafluoride]].<ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[Journal of Fluorine Chemistry]] |doi=10.1016/S0022-1139(00)80734-4 |first=E. A. |last=Lobikov |first2=V. N. |last2=Prusakov |first3=V. F. |last3=Serik |title=Plutonium Hexafluoride Decomposition under the Action of Laser Radiation |date=August-September 1992 |volume=58 |issue=2\u20133 |page=277 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Hexafluorides}}\n{{Plutonium compounds}}\n{{fluorine compounds}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n\n[[Category:Plutonium compounds]]\n[[Category:Hexafluorides]]\n[[Category:Octahedral compounds]]\n[[Category:Metal halides]]\n[[Category:Nuclear materials]]\n", "name_user": "Masum Ibn Musa", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Neptunium(VI)-fluoride-3D-SF.png\u2192File:Neptunium(VI)-fluoride-3D-vdW.pngCriterion 1(original uploader\u2019s request)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plutonium_hexafluoride"}
{"title_page": "Goober Peas", "text_new": "{{about|the traditional folk song|the band|Goober & the Peas}}  ''For the [[Andy Griffith Show]] character, see [[Goober Pyle]].''\n{{Infobox song\n| name      = Goober Peas\n| cover     = GooberPeas1866.png\n| alt       =\n| caption   = Cover, sheet music, 1866\n| type      =\n| language  = English\n| written   =\n| published = 1866\n| writer    =\n| composer  = P. Nutt\n| lyricist  = A. Pindar\n}}\n'''\"Goober Peas\"''' is a traditional [[folk music|folk song]] probably originating in the [[Southern United States]]. It was popular with [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] soldiers during the [[American Civil War]], and is still sung frequently in the South to this day.  It has been recorded and sung by scores of artists, including [[Burl Ives]], [[Tennessee Ernie Ford]] and [[The Kingston Trio]].\n\nThe lyrics of \"Goober Peas\" are a description of daily life during the last few years of the Civil War for Southerners. After being cut off from the rail lines and their farm land, they had little to eat aside from [[boiled peanuts]] (or \"goober peas\") which often served as an emergency ration. Peanuts were also known as pindars and goobers.   As peanuts (or ground nuts) are a common food in West and Central Africa, imported Africans provided these names to the U.S.'s vocabulary.\n\nPublication date on the earliest sheet music is 1866, published by [[Armand Blackmar|A. E. Blackmar]] in New Orleans. Blackmar humorously lists A. Pindar as the lyricist and [[peanut|P. Nutt]] as the composer.<ref>Pindar, \"Goober Peas\".</ref>\n\n==Lyrics==\n''Verse 1''\n:Sitting by the roadside on a summer's day\n:Chatting with my [[mess]]-mates, passing time away\n:Lying in the shadows underneath the trees\n:Goodness, how delicious, eating goober peas.\n\n:''Chorus''\n::Peas, peas, peas, peas\n::Eating goober peas\n::Goodness, how delicious,\n::Eating goober peas.\n\n''Verse 2''\n:When a horse-man passes, the soldiers have a rule\n:To cry out their loudest, \"[[Mister, here's your mule]]!\"\n:But another custom, enchanting-er than these\n:Is wearing out your grinders, eating goober peas.\n:Chorus\n\n''Verse 3''\n:Just before the battle, the General hears a row\n:He says \"The Yanks are coming, I hear their rifles now.\"\n:He turns around in wonder, and what d'ya think he sees?\n:The 15th Alabama, eating goober peas. \n:Chorus\n::(Note: ''There sat the 15th Alambama,'' is reported in contemporary accounts\n\n''Verse 4''\n:I think my song has lasted almost long enough.\n:The subject's interesting, but the rhymes are mighty tough.\n:I wish the war was over, so free from rags and fleas\n:We'd kiss our wives and sweethearts, and gobble goober peas.\n:Chorus\n{{listen|filename=Goober Peas.ogg|title=Goober Peas|description=|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n==Additional verse==\nThe Reverend Wayland Fuller Dunaway recorded a stanza of the song he heard while imprisoned at the Union prison on [[Johnson's Island]], Ohio, during the latter part of the Civil War. Dunaway had been a captain in Co. I, [[40th Virginia Infantry]], when captured during the [[Battle of Williamsport|Battle of Falling Waters]] in July 1863. His stanza:\n:But now we are in prison and likely long to stay,\n:The Yankees they are guarding us, no hope to get away;\n:Our rations they are scanty, 'tis cold enough to freeze,&mdash;\n:I wish I was in Georgia, eating goober peas.\n::Peas, peas, peas, peas,\n::Eating goober peas;\n:I wish I was in Georgia, eating goober peas.\n:::&mdash;''Stanza of a Prison Song.''<ref>Dunaway, ''Reminiscences of a Rebel'', p. 190.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n\n* In [[M*A*S*H]] Season 6 Episode 12 \"Comrades in Arms\", Hawkeye can be heard singing the chorus to himself and explaining to Margaret that it was \"an old Civil War marching song\".{{cn|date=December 2017}}\n* In [[Veep]] Season 3 Episode 3 \"Alecia\", Mike is made to kneel and sing Goober Peas by Jonah in order to not publish a compromising story.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Denise |title=Veep\u2019s Timothy Simons on Jonah\u2019s Near Victory, \u2018Goober Peas,\u2019 and Letterman-Induced Stress Dreams |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/04/timothy-simons-veep-jonah-goober-peas-interview.html |website=Vulture |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n*In the [[Parks and Recreation]] 5th season episode \"Article Two\", Garth ([[Patton Oswalt]]) can be heard singing the chorus.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Dunaway, Wayland Fuller. ''Reminiscences of a Rebel''. New York: The Neale Publishing Company (1913).\n*Pindar, A., Esq. (w.); Nutt, P., Esq. (m.). \"Goober Peas\" (sheet music). New Orleans : A.E. Blackmar (1866).\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|burl-ives|goober-peas}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* [http://jhir.library.jhu.edu/handle/1774.2/12885 Sheet music, in the Levy Sheet Music Collection]\n\n[[Category:American folk songs]]\n[[Category:Songs of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state) in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Burl Ives songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about the military]]\n[[Category:Year of song unknown]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the traditional folk song|the band|Goober & the Peas}}  ''For the [[Andy Griffith Show]] character, see [[Goober Pyle]].''\n{{Infobox song\n| name      = Goober Peas\n| cover     = GooberPeas1866.png\n| alt       =\n| caption   = Cover, sheet music, 1866\n| type      =\n| language  = English\n| written   =\n| published = 1866\n| writer    =\n| composer  = P. Nutt\n| lyricist  = A. Pindar\n}}\n'''\"Goober Peas\"''' is a traditional [[folk music|folk song]] probably originating in the [[Southern United States]]. It was popular with [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] soldiers during the [[American Civil War]], and is still sung frequently in the South to this day.  It has been recorded and sung by scores of artists, including [[Burl Ives]], [[Tennessee Ernie Ford]] and [[The Kingston Trio]].\n\nThe lyrics of \"Goober Peas\" are a description of daily life during the last few years of the Civil War for Southerners. After being cut off from the rail lines and their farm land, they had little to eat aside from [[boiled peanuts]] (or \"goober peas\") which often served as an emergency ration. Peanuts were also known as pindars and goobers.\n\nPublication date on the earliest sheet music is 1866, published by [[Armand Blackmar|A. E. Blackmar]] in New Orleans. Blackmar humorously lists A. Pindar as the lyricist and [[peanut|P. Nutt]] as the composer.<ref>Pindar, \"Goober Peas\".</ref>\n\n==Lyrics==\n''Verse 1''\n:Sitting by the roadside on a summer's day\n:Chatting with my [[mess]]-mates, passing time away\n:Lying in the shadows underneath the trees\n:Goodness, how delicious, eating goober peas.\n\n:''Chorus''\n::Peas, peas, peas, peas\n::Eating goober peas\n::Goodness, how delicious,\n::Eating goober peas.\n\n''Verse 2''\n:When a horse-man passes, the soldiers have a rule\n:To cry out their loudest, \"[[Mister, here's your mule]]!\"\n:But another custom, enchanting-er than these\n:Is wearing out your grinders, eating goober peas.\n:Chorus\n\n''Verse 3''\n:Just before the battle, the General hears a row\n:He says \"The Yanks are coming, I hear their rifles now.\"\n:He turns around in wonder, and what d'ya think he sees?\n:The 15th Alabama, eating goober peas. \n:Chorus\n::(Note: ''There sat the 15th Alambama,'' is reported in contemporary accounts\n\n''Verse 4''\n:I think my song has lasted almost long enough.\n:The subject's interesting, but the rhymes are mighty tough.\n:I wish the war was over, so free from rags and fleas\n:We'd kiss our wives and sweethearts, and gobble goober peas.\n:Chorus\n{{listen|filename=Goober Peas.ogg|title=Goober Peas|description=|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n==Additional verse==\nThe Reverend Wayland Fuller Dunaway recorded a stanza of the song he heard while imprisoned at the Union prison on [[Johnson's Island]], Ohio, during the latter part of the Civil War. Dunaway had been a captain in Co. I, [[40th Virginia Infantry]], when captured during the [[Battle of Williamsport|Battle of Falling Waters]] in July 1863. His stanza:\n:But now we are in prison and likely long to stay,\n:The Yankees they are guarding us, no hope to get away;\n:Our rations they are scanty, 'tis cold enough to freeze,&mdash;\n:I wish I was in Georgia, eating goober peas.\n::Peas, peas, peas, peas,\n::Eating goober peas;\n:I wish I was in Georgia, eating goober peas.\n:::&mdash;''Stanza of a Prison Song.''<ref>Dunaway, ''Reminiscences of a Rebel'', p. 190.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n\n* In [[M*A*S*H]] Season 6 Episode 12 \"Comrades in Arms\", Hawkeye can be heard singing the chorus to himself and explaining to Margaret that it was \"an old Civil War marching song\".{{cn|date=December 2017}}\n* In [[Veep]] Season 3 Episode 3 \"Alecia\", Mike is made to kneel and sing Goober Peas by Jonah in order to not publish a compromising story.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Denise |title=Veep\u2019s Timothy Simons on Jonah\u2019s Near Victory, \u2018Goober Peas,\u2019 and Letterman-Induced Stress Dreams |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/04/timothy-simons-veep-jonah-goober-peas-interview.html |website=Vulture |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n*In the [[Parks and Recreation]] 5th season episode \"Article Two\", Garth ([[Patton Oswalt]]) can be heard singing the chorus.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Dunaway, Wayland Fuller. ''Reminiscences of a Rebel''. New York: The Neale Publishing Company (1913).\n*Pindar, A., Esq. (w.); Nutt, P., Esq. (m.). \"Goober Peas\" (sheet music). New Orleans : A.E. Blackmar (1866).\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|burl-ives|goober-peas}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* [http://jhir.library.jhu.edu/handle/1774.2/12885 Sheet music, in the Levy Sheet Music Collection]\n\n[[Category:American folk songs]]\n[[Category:Songs of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state) in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Burl Ives songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about the military]]\n[[Category:Year of song unknown]]\n", "name_user": "TempeRed3", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a sentence on African origin of the word \"goober\", and groundnuts' use in Africa.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goober_Peas"}
{"title_page": "Nikola Kotkov", "text_new": "{{short description|Bulgarian footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Nikola Kotkov\n| fullname = Nikola Todorov Kotkov\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1938|12|9}}\n| birth_place = [[Sofia]], Bulgaria\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1971|6|30|1938|12|9}}\n| death_place = Sofia, Bulgaria\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| youthyears1 =  \n| youthclubs1 = [[FC Lokomotiv 1929 Sofia|Lokomotiv Sofia]]\n| years1 =  1956\u20131968 | clubs1 = [[FC Lokomotiv 1929 Sofia|Lokomotiv Sofia]] | caps1 = 274 | goals1 = 143 \n| years2 =  1969      | clubs2 = ZHSK Slavia                                 | caps2 = 12  | goals2 = 2\n| years3 =  1969\u20131971 | clubs3 = [[PFC Levski Sofia|Levski Sofia]]           | caps3 = 36  | goals3 = 18\n| totalcaps =  322 | totalgoals =  163\n| nationalteam1 =   [[Bulgaria national under-19 football team|Bulgaria U19]] \n| nationalteam2 =  [[Bulgaria national under-21 football team|Bulgaria U21]] \n| nationalteam3 =  [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] \n| nationalyears1 =  1956\u20131959 \n| nationalyears2 =  1959\u20131961 \n| nationalyears3 =  1961\u20131969\n| nationalcaps1 =    16  \n| nationalcaps2 =  7  \n| nationalcaps3 =  26   \n| nationalgoals1 =   8   \n| nationalgoals2 =   5   \n| nationalgoals3 =   12   \n| pcupdate = December 2006\n| ntupdate = December 2006\n}}\n\n'''Nikola Todorov Kotkov''' ({{lang-bg|\u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u0422\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u041a\u043e\u0442\u043a\u043e\u0432}}) (9 December 1938 \u2013 30 June 1971), nicknamed '''Koteto''' (\u041a\u043e\u0442\u0435\u0442\u043e, \"The [[Kitten]]\") was a [[Bulgaria]]n [[football (soccer)|footballer]] who played as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]].\n\nBorn in the capital [[Sofia]], Kotkov started his football career as a [[PFC Lokomotiv Sofia|Lokomotiv Sofia]] trainee and went on to spend much of it (1956\u20131969) with the club, winning the [[Bulgarian Championship]] in 1964. He then played for [[PFC Levski Sofia|Levski Sofia]], until his death in 1971. Kotkov died together with his friend and teammate [[Georgi Asparuhov]] in a [[traffic accident]] in the Vitinya Pass of the [[Balkan Mountains]], en route to [[Vratsa]]. With Levski, Kotkov became once again champion in 1970, winning the [[Bulgarian Cup]] [[Double (association football)|the same year]].\n\nKotkov played a total of 322 matches and scored 163 goals in the Bulgarian Championship and was given the [[Bulgarian Footballer of the Year]] award in 1964. For the [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria national team]], he had 26 caps and scored 12 goals, taking part in the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]] in [[England]].\n\nA fan favourite noted for his fair play, Kotkov was known for his remarkable technique, pinpoint passing and skillful free kick taking.\n\n== Statistics ==\n* National teams \u2014 59 matches, 33 goals\n* Bulgarian championship \u2014 322 matches, 163 goals \u2014 286/145 for Lokomotiv,  45/25 for Levski\n* European club tournaments \u2014 11 matches, 10 goals \u2014 CEC-6, CWC-5\n* First match \u2014 with Lokomotiv Sofia 1956\n* Last match \u2014 with Levski against CSKA \u2014 28 June 1971\n* '''All - 392 matches, 206 goals'''\n\n== Honours ==\n* Champion of Bulgaria \u2014 2 times, 1964 with Lokomotiv and 1970 with Levski\n* Holder of the National Cup \u2014 2 times 1970, 1971 (posthumously) with Levski\n* [[Bulgarian Footballer of the Year]] \u2014 1964\n* [[UEFA European Under-19 Championship|UEFA Euro Under-19]] Champion with [[Bulgaria national under-19 football team|Bulgaria]] \u2014 [[1959 UEFA European Under-18 Championship|1959]]\n* Holder of an Order of Labour \u2014 1970\n* Deserved Master of Sports\n* 25th place in the [[Ballon d'Or (1956\u20132009)|Golden Ball]] quiz \u2014 [[1967 Ballon d'Or|1967]]\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite book | last = Paytashev | first = Rumen | year = 2001 | title = Svetovna Futbolna Entsiklopediya | publisher = KK Trud | location = Sofia | isbn = 978-954-528-201-0 | page = 187 }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ultrasloko.com/legends/legends_kotkov_bg.html Article about Kotkov from a PFC Lokomotiv Sofia fansite] {{in lang|bg}}\n* [http://en.levskisofia.info/player/nikola-kotkov/ Profile at LevskiSofia.info]\n\n{{Bulgarian Footballer of the Year}}\n{{Bulgaria Squad 1966 World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kotkov, Nikola}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian footballers]]\n[[Category:Bulgaria international footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Lokomotiv 1929 Sofia players]]\n[[Category:PFC Levski Sofia players]]\n[[Category:First Professional Football League (Bulgaria) players]]\n[[Category:1966 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sofia]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:20th-century Bulgarian people]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n\n{{bulgaria-footy-forward-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Nikola Kotkov\n| fullname = Nikola Todorov Kotkov\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1938|12|9}}\n| birth_place = [[Sofia]], Bulgaria\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1971|6|30|1938|12|9}}\n| death_place = Sofia, Bulgaria\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| youthyears1 =  \n| youthclubs1 = [[FC Lokomotiv 1929 Sofia|Lokomotiv Sofia]]\n| years1 =  1956\u20131968 | clubs1 = [[FC Lokomotiv 1929 Sofia|Lokomotiv Sofia]] | caps1 = 274 | goals1 = 143 \n| years2 =  1969      | clubs2 = ZHSK Slavia                                 | caps2 = 12  | goals2 = 2\n| years3 =  1969\u20131971 | clubs3 = [[PFC Levski Sofia|Levski Sofia]]           | caps3 = 36  | goals3 = 18\n| totalcaps =  322 | totalgoals =  163\n| nationalteam1 =   [[Bulgaria national under-19 football team|Bulgaria U19]] \n| nationalteam2 =  [[Bulgaria national under-21 football team|Bulgaria U21]] \n| nationalteam3 =  [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] \n| nationalyears1 =  1956\u20131959 \n| nationalyears2 =  1959\u20131961 \n| nationalyears3 =  1961\u20131969\n| nationalcaps1 =    16  \n| nationalcaps2 =  7  \n| nationalcaps3 =  26   \n| nationalgoals1 =   8   \n| nationalgoals2 =   5   \n| nationalgoals3 =   12   \n| pcupdate = December 2006\n| ntupdate = December 2006\n}}\n\n'''Nikola Todorov Kotkov''' ({{lang-bg|\u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u0422\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u041a\u043e\u0442\u043a\u043e\u0432}}) (9 December 1938 \u2013 30 June 1971), nicknamed '''Koteto''' (\u041a\u043e\u0442\u0435\u0442\u043e, \"The [[Kitten]]\") was a [[Bulgaria]]n [[football (soccer)|footballer]] who played as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]].\n\nBorn in the capital [[Sofia]], Kotkov started his football career as a [[PFC Lokomotiv Sofia|Lokomotiv Sofia]] trainee and went on to spend much of it (1956\u20131969) with the club, winning the [[Bulgarian Championship]] in 1964. He then played for [[PFC Levski Sofia|Levski Sofia]], until his death in 1971. Kotkov died together with his friend and teammate [[Georgi Asparuhov]] in a [[traffic accident]] in the Vitinya Pass of the [[Balkan Mountains]], en route to [[Vratsa]]. With Levski, Kotkov became once again champion in 1970, winning the [[Bulgarian Cup]] [[Double (association football)|the same year]].\n\nKotkov played a total of 322 matches and scored 163 goals in the Bulgarian Championship and was given the [[Bulgarian Footballer of the Year]] award in 1964. For the [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria national team]], he had 26 caps and scored 12 goals, taking part in the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]] in [[England]].\n\nA fan favourite noted for his fair play, Kotkov was known for his remarkable technique, pinpoint passing and skillful free kick taking.\n\n== Statistics ==\n* National teams \u2014 59 matches, 33 goals\n* Bulgarian championship \u2014 322 matches, 163 goals \u2014 286/145 for Lokomotiv,  45/25 for Levski\n* European club tournaments \u2014 11 matches, 10 goals \u2014 CEC-6, CWC-5\n* First match \u2014 with Lokomotiv Sofia 1956\n* Last match \u2014 with Levski against CSKA \u2014 28 June 1971\n* '''All - 392 matches, 206 goals'''\n\n== Honours ==\n* Champion of Bulgaria \u2014 2 times, 1964 with Lokomotiv and 1970 with Levski\n* Holder of the National Cup \u2014 2 times 1970, 1971 (posthumously) with Levski\n* [[Bulgarian Footballer of the Year]] \u2014 1964\n* [[UEFA European Under-19 Championship|UEFA Euro Under-19]] Champion with [[Bulgaria national under-19 football team|Bulgaria]] \u2014 [[1959 UEFA European Under-18 Championship|1959]]\n* Holder of an Order of Labour \u2014 1970\n* Deserved Master of Sports\n* 25th place in the [[Ballon d'Or (1956\u20132009)|Golden Ball]] quiz \u2014 [[1967 Ballon d'Or|1967]]\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite book | last = Paytashev | first = Rumen | year = 2001 | title = Svetovna Futbolna Entsiklopediya | publisher = KK Trud | location = Sofia | isbn = 978-954-528-201-0 | page = 187 }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ultrasloko.com/legends/legends_kotkov_bg.html Article about Kotkov from a PFC Lokomotiv Sofia fansite] {{in lang|bg}}\n* [http://en.levskisofia.info/player/nikola-kotkov/ Profile at LevskiSofia.info]\n\n{{Bulgarian Footballer of the Year}}\n{{Bulgaria Squad 1966 World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kotkov, Nikola}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian footballers]]\n[[Category:Bulgaria international footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Lokomotiv 1929 Sofia players]]\n[[Category:PFC Levski Sofia players]]\n[[Category:First Professional Football League (Bulgaria) players]]\n[[Category:1966 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sofia]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:20th-century Bulgarian people]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n\n{{bulgaria-footy-forward-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\