1|language=Korean|publisher=TV Report|date=October 24, 2013|accessdate=November 20, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[SBS Entertainment Awards]]\n| New Rookie Award (MC Category)\n| ''TV Entertainment Tonight''\n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=011&aid=0002445936|title=SBS \uc5f0\uc608\ub300\uc0c1 '\uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1' \uc218\uc601, \uc218\uc0c1 \uc778\uc99d\uc0f7 \"\uc601\uad11\uc758 \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1\"|publisher=Hankooki|date=December 31, 2013|accessdate=May 28, 2015|language=Korean}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2014\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[2014 MBC Drama Awards|MBC Drama Awards]]\n| Excellence Award, Actress in a Miniseries \n| rowspan=\"3\"|''[[My Spring Days]]''\n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2014123100223539274&outlink=2&SVEC|title=\ud0dc\uc5f0\u00b7\uc368\ub2c8, \uc218\uc601 MBC\uc5f0\uae30\ub300\uc0c1 \uc6b0\uc218 \uc5f0\uae30\uc0c1 \ucd95\ud558|language=Korean|publisher=Star News|date=December 31, 2014|accessdate=May 28, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Couple Award\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imbc.com/broad/tv/ent/event/2014mbc/couple/index.html|title=2014 MBC Drama Award Nominees for \"Best Couple\"|language=Korean|date=December 2014|accessdate=May 28, 2015|publisher=MBC}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015 \n| [[8th Korea Drama Awards]] \n| Excellence Award, Actress \n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=koreanaward2015>{{cite news|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2015090909282924799|title=\uae40\uc218\ud604vs\uc8fc\uc6d0, 2015 \ucf54\ub9ac\uc544\ub4dc\ub77c\ub9c8\uc5b4\uc6cc\uc988 \ub300\uc0c1 \uaca9\ub3cc|language=Korean|publisher=Star News|date=September 9, 2015|accessdate=September 18, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017 \n| [[2017 MBC Drama Awards]] \n| Excellence Award, Actress \n|''[[Man in the Kitchen]]''\n| {{nominated}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2019 \n| 15th [[Jecheon International Music & Film Festival]] \n| Discovery of the Year Award \n|''Memories of a Dead End''\n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/1344500wpp/exos-suho-and-girls-generations-sooyoung-receive-jimff-awards|title=EXO\u2019s Suho And Girls\u2019 Generation\u2019s Sooyoung Receive JIMFF Awards|publisher=Soompi|date=August 9, 2019|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[40th Blue Dragon Film Awards]] \n| Best New Actress\n|''[[Miss & Mrs. Cops]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=076&aid=0003499598 |title=[\uc81c40\ud68c \uccad\ub8e1\uc601\ud654\uc0c1]'\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9' \ub3c5\uc8fcvs\ubc18\uc804\uc758 \uacb0\uacfc'\u2026\uccad\ub8e1D-day, \ud6c4\ubcf4\ubcc4 \uad00\uc804 \ud3ec\uc778\ud2b8 |date=November 21, 2019 |work=Sports Chosun |author=\uc774\uc2b9\ubbf8  |language=Korean}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--per [[WP:EL]], ONE official website is allowed. Pick one and that's it. This is not an SNS directory.-->\n{{Commons category|Choi Soo-young}}\n* {{IMDB person|id=3210659}}\n* {{HanCinema person}}\n\n{{Girls' Generation}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Choi, Soo-young}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gyeonggi Province]]\n[[Category:Girls' Generation members]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language singers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:South Korean female idols]]\n[[Category:South Korean female pop singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:South Korean film actresses]]\n[[Category:South Korean television actresses]]\n[[Category:South Korean television presenters]]\n[[Category:Chung-Ang University alumni]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from South Korea]]\n[[Category:Mandarin-language singers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:21st-century South Korean actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South Korean singer and actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{For|the given name (and other people with the given name)|Soo-young (name)}}\n{{Korean name|Choi}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Choi Soo-young\n| image           = Choi Soo-young at AmieMarket on February 23, 2018 (2).jpg\n| caption         = Choi in February 2018\n| native_name     = \ucd5c\uc218\uc601\n| birth_name      = Choi Soo-young\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1990|02|10}}\n| birth_place     = [[Gwangju, Gyeonggi]], South Korea\n| alma_mater      = [[Chung-Ang University]]\n| occupation = {{hlist|Singer|actress|songwriter}}\n| agent           = [[Saram Entertainment]]\n| module          = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = [[K-pop]]\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| years_active    = 2002\u2013present\n| label           = [[SM Entertainment|SM]]\n| associated_acts = [[Girls' Generation]]\n}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| title           = [[Korean name]]\n| hangul          = \ucd5c\uc218\uc601\n| hanja           = {{linktext|\u5d14|\u79c0|\u69ae}}\n| rr              = Choe Su-yeong\n| mr              = Ch'oe Suy\u014fng\n}}\n\n'''Choi Soo-young''' (born February 10, 1990), professionally known as '''Sooyoung''', is a South Korean singer, actress and songwriter. She was a member of the short-lived Korean-Japanese singing duo [[Route 0 (group)|Route 0]] during 2002 in Japan. After returning to South Korea in 2004, Sooyoung eventually became a member of girl group [[Girls' Generation]] in 2007, which went on to become one of the best-selling artists in South Korea and one of South Korea's most popular girl groups worldwide. Apart from her group's activities, Sooyoung has also starred in various [[Korean drama|television dramas]] such as ''[[The Third Hospital]]'' (2012), ''[[Dating Agency: Cyrano]]'' (2013), ''[[My Spring Days]]'' (2014), ''[[Squad 38]]'' (2016), and ''[[Man in the Kitchen]]'' (2017\u20132018).\n\nIn October 2017, Sooyoung left [[SM Entertainment]] although she remains as a member of Girls' Generation. She joined Echo Global Group and released her first solo single \"Winter Breath\" in 2018, before moving to [[Saram Entertainment]] in 2019.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===1990\u20132007: Early life and career beginnings===\nSooyoung was born in [[Gwangju, Gyeonggi]], South Korea, on February 10, 1990.<ref name=\"Russell2014\">{{cite book|author=Mark Russell|title=K-Pop Now!: The Korean Music Revolution|page=72|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=etDZAwAAQBAJ|date=29 April 2014|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=978-1-4629-1411-1}}</ref> She is the younger sister of [[Choi Soo-jin]], who is a musical theatre actress.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/foreign/starViewEng.html?no=2012092015441896273|title=SNSD's Sooyoung and her sister love the same man on a TV series|publisher=StarNews|date=September 20, 2012|accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref> Sooyoung was initially discovered through an [[SM Entertainment]] Open Audition when she was in fifth grade.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20140828n06267|title=\uc218\uc601 \"4\uc77c\uac04 SM\uc9c1\uc6d0 4\uba85\uc5d0\uac8c \uae38\uac70\ub9ac\uce90\uc2a4\ud305 \ub410\ub2e4\"|publisher=Newsen|date=August 28, 2014|accessdate=July 15, 2015}}</ref> She later won first place at the 2002 Korea-Japan Ultra Idol Duo Audition and debuted in Japan as a member of [[Route 0 (group)|Route 0]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=081&aid=0002130347||title=\uc18c\ub140\uc2dc\ub300 \uc218\uc601, VJ\uc2dc\uc808-\uc77c\ubcf8\uc720\ub2db '\uacfc\uac70\uc0ac\uc9c4' \ub208\uae38|language=Korean|date=November 2, 2010|accessdate=July 20, 2015|publisher=Naver}}</ref> The duo released three singles before disbanding in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041204234318/http://www.randc.jp/route0/discography.html|url=http://www.randc.jp/route0/discography.html|archivedate=December 4, 2004|title=Route0 Discography}}</ref> Sooyoung returned to SM Entertainment and eventually debuted in South Korea as a member of the girl group [[Girls' Generation]] in August 2007. The group gained significant popularity with the release of their hit single \"[[Gee (Girls' Generation song)|Gee]]\" in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|first=Do-yeun|last=Kim|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2011/11/135_97862.html|title=Girls' Generation featured on Yale School of Art website|date=November 2, 2011|accessdate=February 28, 2015|publisher=Korea Times}}</ref>  Sooyoung has said in an interview that she was also interested in acting before debuting as a singer and had failed more than 70 auditions during her pre-debut days.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/16041/interview-snsds-sooyoung-wants-to-live-her-life-in-comfort|title=SNSD\u2032s Sooyoung Wants to Live Her Life in Comfort|date=September 30, 2012|author=Erika Kim|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=eNewsWorld|publisher=[[CJ E&M]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409150713/http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/16041/interview-snsds-sooyoung-wants-to-live-her-life-in-comfort|archive-date=April 9, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===2008\u20132016: Acting roles and lyrics writing===\nAside from Girls' Generation's activities, Sooyoung has participated in various music and acting projects. In the early days, her acting work mostly involved several small roles and guest appearances\u2014these include [[KBS2]]'s sitcom ''[[Unstoppable Marriage (TV series)|Unstoppable Marriage]]'' (2007),<ref name=marriage>{{cite news|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2007110310002347244&type=1&outlink=1|title=\uc18c\ub140\uc2dc\ub300 \uc218\uc601\u318d\uc720\ub9ac, 3\ub144\uc804\ubd80\ud130 \uc5f0\uae30\uc900\ube44|language=Korean|date=November 3, 2007|publisher=StarNews|accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref> romantic comedy film ''[[Hello, Schoolgirl]]'' (2008),<ref name=hello>{{cite news|url=http://news.donga.com/3/all/20081128/8664143/1|title=\uc18c\ub140\uc2dc\ub300 \uc218\uc601, '\uc21c\uc815\ub9cc\ud654'\ub85c \uc2a4\ud06c\ub9b0 \uc2e0\uace0\uc2dd|publisher=[[The Dong-a Ilbo]]|date=November 28, 2008|accessdate=March 29, 2016|language=Korean}}</ref> SBS's drama ''[[Oh! My Lady]]'' (2010),<ref name=lady>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=201004122245381001|title='\uc624\ub9c8\uc774 \ub808\uc774\ub514' \uc18c\ub140\uc2dc\ub300 3\uc778\ubc29 \uc81c\uc2dc\uce74 \ud6a8\uc5f0 \uc218\uc601 '\uae5c\uc9dd \ub4f1\uc7a5'|date=April 12, 2010|publisher=Newsen|accessdate=March 29, 2016|language=ko}}</ref> SBS's ''[[Paradise Ranch]]'' (2011) and SBS's ''[[A Gentleman's Dignity]]'' (2012).<ref name=paradise>{{cite news|url=http://sports.chosun.com/news/ntype.htm?id=201102020100007790000091&servicedate=20110201|title='\ud30c\ub77c\ub2e4\uc774\uc2a4 \ubaa9\uc7a5' \uc218\uc601 \uae5c\uc9dd \ucd9c\uc5f0, \uc2ec\ucc3d\ubbfc \ubc18\uc131\ubb38 \uccb4\ud06c|date=February 1, 2011|accessdate=March 29, 2016|language=ko|publisher=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]}}</ref><ref name=gentleman /> During this period, musically, she recorded two songs\u2014one trot song titled \"KKok\" with Girls' Generation member [[Kwon Yuri|Yuri]] for the [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]' drama ''[[Working Mom (TV series)|Working Mom]]'', while the other one, \"Feeling Only You\", was a collaboration with Girls' Generation member [[Tiffany Hwang|Tiffany]] and South Korean duo The Blue.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200808080913591002|title=\uc18c\ub140\uc2dc\ub300 \uc720\ub9ac-\uc218\uc601 '\uc6cc\ud0b9\ub9d8' OST \ud2b8\ub85c\ud2b8 \ub3c4\uc804 \ud654\uc81c|date=August 8, 2008|publisher=Newsen|accessdate=March 29, 2016|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200905121333041001|title=\ub354 \ube14\ub8e8, \ud2f0\ud30c\ub2c8-\uc218\uc601\uacfc \ud568\uaed8 \ud55c UCC \uacf5\uac1c '\ud6c8\ud6c8'|date=May 12, 2009|accessdate=March 29, 2016|language=korean|publisher=Newsen}}</ref> Throughout her career, besides contributing her vocal to Girls' Generation's songs, Sooyoung has explored into lyrics writing. She penned the lyrics for three songs: \"[[The Boys (Girls' Generation album)|How Great is Your Love]]\" (2011),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2942939|title=With new album, Girls' Generation grows up|date=October 19, 2011|publisher=[[JoongAng Ilbo]]|accessdate=April 14, 2016|author=Sung So-young}}</ref> \"[[I Just Wanna Dance (EP)#Track listing|What Do I Do]]\" (2016),<ref>{{cite video|title=Pops in Seoul _ Tiffany(\ud2f0\ud30c\ub2c8) _ Interview _ Part 1|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DOGsSbZxD9s|publisher=[[Arirang (TV network)|Arirang]] on YouTube / Google Inc|location=South Korea|accessdate=June 5, 2016|format=news program|date=May 23, 2016}}</ref> and \"Sailing (0805)\" (2016),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/7461795/girls-generation-9th-anniversary-sailing|title=Girls' Generation Celebrates 9th Anniversary With 'Sailing'|work=Billboard|first=Tamar|last=Herman|date=August 5, 2016|access-date=August 5, 2016}}</ref> while co-writing the song \"[[I Got a Boy|Baby Maybe]]\" (2013).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=20121231000109&md=20130103004024_BL|title=\uc18c\ub140\uc2dc\ub300, \uc815\uaddc4\uc9d1 'I Got a Boy'\u2026\uc218\uc601\u318d\uc720\ub9ac\u318d\uc11c\ud604 \uc791\uc0ac \ucc38\uc5ec, \ud0dc\uc5f0\u318d\ud2f0\ud30c\ub2c8 \ub4c0\uc5e3\uace1 \uc218\ub85d|date=December 31, 2012|publisher=Herald Corporation|language=Korean|accessdate=June 2, 2015}}</ref> \n\nIn September 2012, she landed her first major acting role in [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]]'s medical drama ''[[The Third Hospital]]''.<ref name=hospital>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/10296|title=Girls' Generation Sooyoung cast in tvN's medical series|date=March 20, 2012|website=10Asia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2958661|title=Sooyoung hopes to sing for her drama|date=August 31, 2012|publisher=[[JoongAng Ilbo]]|accessdate=March 28, 2016|author=Carla Sunwoo}}</ref> She was praised by both co-actors [[Oh Ji Ho]] and [[Kim Seung-woo]] and the viewers were drawn to her emotional scene due to her natural display of emotion.<ref>{{cite news|title=The 3rd Hospital Interview|publisher=The Singles Magazine - September 2012 Issue|date=September 2012|language=Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://etv.sbs.co.kr/news/news_content.jsp?article_id=E10001332757|title='\uc81c3\ubcd1\uc6d0' \uc218\uc601, \ubb3c\uc624\ub978 \ub208\ubb3c\uc5f0\uae30\uc5d0 \uc2dc\uccad\uc790\ub3c4 \ub180\ub790\ub2e4|date=October 11, 2012|publisher=[[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]|accessdate=March 29, 2016|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.soompi.com/2012/10/11/girls-generations-sooyoung-receiving-recognition-for-her-great-acting/||title=Girls' Generation's Sooyoung Receiving Recognition For Her Great Acting|date=October 11, 2012|accessdate=July 20, 2015|publisher=Soompi}}</ref>{{better source needed|date= May 2018}} In May 2013, Sooyoung was cast in tvN's romantic comedy drama, ''[[Dating Agency: Cyrano]]''. It was a spin-off of the 2010 movie ''[[Cyrano Agency]]''. She played a dating expert who works at a dating agency helping people to find their love.<ref name=dating>{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2972022|title=Cast gathers to hype \"Cyrano\"|date=May 24, 2013|publisher=[[JoongAng Ilbo]]|accessdate=March 28, 2016|author=Lee Sun-min}}</ref> Park Ju-yeon from the ''[[Hankook Ilbo]]'' praised Sooyoung for her lively character portrayal and said that there was not any \"overdone emotions commonly appear in acting newcomers\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://reviewstar.hankooki.com/Article/ArticleView.php?WEB_GSNO=10113272|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130809083122/http://reviewstar.hankooki.com/Article/ArticleView.php?WEB_GSNO=10113272|title='\uc2dc\ub77c\ub178', \ud640\ub85c\uc11c\uae30 \uc218\uc601, \uc5f0\uae30 \uc774 \uc815\ub3c4\uc600\ub098?|date=May 29, 2013|archivedate=August 9, 2013|publisher=[[Hankook Ilbo]]|language=Ko|author=Park Ju-yeon}}</ref>\nIn September 2014, Sooyoung scored a lead role in [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]'s melodrama, ''[[My Spring Days]]''. Her character is a terminally ill patient who gets a heart transplant; and meets her donor's husband, played by [[Kam Woo-sung]].<ref name=spring>{{Cite news|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20140717000931_2 |title=Girls' Generation's Sooyoung to be heroine of upcoming drama|author=Ock Hyun-ju |publisher=[[The Korea Herald]] |date=July 17, 2014 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> This was a breakthrough performance for Sooyoung as she won the \"Best Actress in a Miniseries\" award at the 2014 [[MBC Drama Awards]] and the \"Excellence Award for Actress\" at the 2015 [[Korea Drama Awards]].<ref name=spring/><ref name=koreanaward2015/> She contributed a song to its soundtrack, titled \"Wind Flower\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2014103008200398205&type=1&outlink=1|title=\uc218\uc601, '\ub0b4\uc0dd\uc560 \ubd04\ub0a0' OST \ucc38\uc5ec..30\uc77c '\ubc14\ub78c\uaf43' \uacf5\uac1c|publisher=StarNews|date=October 30, 2014|accessdate=March 29, 2016|language=korean}}</ref> In 2015, Sooyoung starred as the female lead in KBS2's special drama ''Perfect Sense'', which was produced by [[Samsung Fire & Marine Insurance]] to help raise public understanding of the disabled. She played a teacher named  who is visually impaired.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/biz/2015/12/602_192454.html|title=\tInsurer helps teenager better understand the disabled|date=December 4, 2015|accessdate=March 28, 2016|publisher=The Korea Times}}</ref><ref name=perfect>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3017381|title=Sooyoung cast in drama about the disabled|date=April 12, 2016|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref> In June 2016, Sooyoung starred as the female lead alongside [[Ma Dong-seok]] and [[Seo In-guk]] in the OCN crime drama ''[[Squad 38]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/ranking/read?oid=076&aid=0002876234|title=\ub2e8\ub3c5\uc11c\uc778\uad6d\u00b7\uc218\uc601\u00b7\ub9c8\ub3d9\uc11d '38\uc0ac\uae30\ub3d9\ub300' \ucd9c\uc5f0\u2026\uc81c2\uc758 '\ub098\uc05c\ub140\uc11d\ub4e4'|publisher=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|date=January 18, 2016|accessdate=March 29, 2016|language=korean}}</ref><ref name=\"ocn\">{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3015758|title=Sooyoung, others to star in new OCN drama|date=March 4, 2016|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017\u2013present: Departure from SM Entertainment and solo activities ===\nIn early August 2017, Sooyoung starred as television producer in the [[JTBC]] web drama ''Someone You Might Know''.<ref name=\"someone\">{{cite news|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201708011647009558611_2|title=Sooyoung thinks of her boyfriend's death while filming new drama|author=Kim So-yeon|publisher=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=August 1, 2017|accessdate=September 8, 2017}}</ref> Later in August, she played the female lead in the MBC drama series ''[[Man in the Kitchen]]''.<ref name=\"kitchen\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/choi-soo-young-and-on-joo-wan-in-man-who-lays-the-table-105864.html|title=Choi Soo-young and On Joo-wan in \"Man Who Lays the Table\"|date=May 11, 2017|website=Hancinema|publisher=Newsen}}</ref> In November 2017, Sooyoung joined Echo Global Group after her contract with SM Entertainment ended. With a change of label, her future activities with Girls' Generation remain in discussion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20171010000173|title=Girls' Generation's Tiffany, Sooyoung and Seohyun to leave S.M. Entertainment: sources|date=October 10, 2017|publisher=The Korea Herald|access-date=October 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nwww.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20171110000710|title=Sooyoung of Girls' Generation signs with Daniel Henney's agency|date=November 10, 2017|publisher=Yonhap News Agency|access-date=November 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Sooyoung was cast in the Korean-Japanese film ''Memories of a Dead End'',<ref name=memories>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201803221153133120227_2|title=Choi Soo-young to star in 'Memories of a Dead End'|date=March 22, 2018|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/news.jsp?pageIndex=1&blbdComCd=601006&seq=4767&mode=VIEW&returnUrl=&searchKeyword=Soo-young|title=CHOI Soo-young of Girls' Generation Lands First Lead Role|date=April 3, 2018|website=Korean Film Biz Zone}}</ref> the action comedy film ''[[Girl Cops]]'',<ref name=girl>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201807091710003929482_2|title=Casting complete for new film 'Girl Cops'|date=July 9, 2018|website=Kpop Herald|publisher=Herald Corporation}}</ref> and the romantic comedy television series ''[[So I Married an Anti-fan (TV series)|So I Married an Anti-fan]]'', based on the manhwa of the same name, alongside [[Choi Tae-joon]].<ref name=anti>{{cite web|url=https://news.sbs.co.kr/news/endPage.do?news_id=N1004888295|title=[SBS Star] Sooyoung & Choi Tae Jun Confirmed to a New Drama|date=August 13, 2018|website=SBS News}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Sooyoung released her solo single, \"Winter Breath,\" which is her first song to be released since her departure from SM Entertainment, with the song's music video made available online on the same day. Sooyoung launched her official Twitter and YouTube accounts to commemorate the single's release.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201812201615316551691_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Sooyoung of Girls' Generation breaks hiatus from music, debuts solo|date=December 20, 2018|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201812281322580260877_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Sooyoung looks back on decade with Girls' Generation|date=December 28, 2018|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Sooyoung signed with new agency Saram Entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://star.hankookilbo.com/News/Read/201905070816790018?did=NA&dtype=&dtypecode=&prnewsid=|title=\ucd5c\uc218\uc601 \"\uc0ac\ub78c\uc5d4\ud130\uc640 \uc804\uc18d\uacc4\uc57d, \uae30\uc058\uace0 \uae30\ub300\ub3fc\uc694\" |language=Korean |trans-title=Sooyoung: \"I'm Excited About My Exclusive Contract with Saram Entertainment\" |date=May 7, 2019|website=Korea Times |access-date=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Sooyoung starred in the OCN drama ''[[ Tell Me What You Saw]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news1.kr/articles/?3753143|title=\ucd5c\uc218\uc601 \"'\ubcf8\ub300\ub85c \ub9d0\ud558\ub77c' \uc7a5\ud601\uacfc\uc758 \ud638\ud761, \uc601\uad11\uc774\uace0 \ud589\uc6b4\"|website=Naver|publisher=News1|accessdate=October 25, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSince 2015, Sooyoung has held an annual charity auction event called \"Beaming Effect\", to raise money for finding a cure for [[retinitis pigmentosa]], a disease that her father suffers from.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201501271713469897083_2|title=SNSD'S Sooyoung shows love for RP patients|author=Yoon Sarah|publisher=[[The Korea Herald|Kpop Herald]]|date=January 27, 2015|accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201603201439016703461_2|title=SNSD Sooyoung holds charity auction|author=Jung Min-kyung|publisher=Kpop Herald|date=March 20, 2016|accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=201302131153592310|title=\uc218\uc601 \uc544\ubc84\uc9c0 \ud22c\ubcd1 \ub9dd\ub9c9\uc0c9\uc18c\ubcc0\uc131\uc99d \uc5b4\ub5a4 \uc9c8\ud658? '\ud6c4\ucc9c\uc131 3\ub300\uc2e4\uba85\uc6d0\uc778'|date=February 13, 2013|publisher=Newsen|accessdate=March 29, 2016|language=korean}}</ref>\n\nSooyoung graduated from JeongShin Women's High School in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://foto.sportschosun.com/news/ntype2_o.htm?ut=1&name=/news/entertainment/200902/20090212/92l77128.htm|title='\uace0\uad50 \uc878\uc5c5' \uc18c\ub140\uc2dc\ub300\uc758 \uc724\uc544-\uc218\uc601, \"3\uc6d4\ubd80\ud130 \ucea0\ud37c\uc2a4\uc5d0\uc11c \ub9cc\ub098\uc694\"|publisher=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|date=February 11, 2009|accessdate=July 15, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717043500/http://foto.sportschosun.com/news/ntype2_o.htm?ut=1&name=%2Fnews%2Fentertainment%2F200902%2F20090212%2F92l77128.htm|archivedate=July 17, 2015}}</ref>  She went on to major in film studies and graduated from [[Chung-Ang University]] in February 2016, receiving a lifetime achievement award at the graduation ceremony.  Her fellow Girls' Generation member [[Kwon Yuri]] attended the same university.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201602111704519605601_2|title=Stars get B.A. degrees from ChungAng Univ.|date=February 10, 2016|author=Kim Soo-hyang|accessdate=March 28, 2016|publisher=[[The Korea Herald]]}}</ref>\n\nSooyoung has been dating [[Jung Kyung-ho (actor, born 1983)|Jung Kyung-ho]] since 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Soo-young and Jung Kyung-ho Officially an Item|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2014/01/06/2014010600642.html|publisher=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|accessdate=2014-01-09|date=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Girls' Generation discography}}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album \n! Song\n! Duration\n! Artist\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Inuyasha]] OST''\n| \"I Am\" (Korean Version)\n| 01:24\n| Solo\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Working Mom (TV series)#Original soundtrack|Working Mom OST]]''\n| \"KKok\"\n| 03:24\n| Duet with [[Kwon Yuri]]\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''The First Memories''\n| \"Feeling Only You\"\n| 03:26\n| [[The Blue (musical duo)|The Blue]] (feat. [[Tiffany Hwang|Tiffany]] and Sooyoung)\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[My Spring Days]] OST''\n| \"Wind Flower\"\n| 03:29\n| Solo\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2018\n| ''The Light''\n| \"Let's Get Away\"\n| 03:57\n| James Lee (feat. Sooyoung)\n|-\n| ''Winter Breath''\n| \"Winter Breath\"\n| 03:51\n| Solo\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Girls' Generation filmography}}\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Hello, Schoolgirl#TV series (2008 film)|Hello, Schoolgirl]]''\n| Jeong Da-jeong\n| Supporting role\n| <ref name=hello /> \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[I AM.]]''\n| Herself\n| Biographical film of SM Town\n| <ref>{{cite news|title=Documentary Shows Top K-Pop Singers Behind the Scenes|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/05/02/2012050200829.html|accessdate=May 4, 2012|publisher=The Chosun Ilbo|date=May 2, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''SMTown: The Stage''\n| Herself\n| Documentary film of SM Town\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.entertain.naver.com/read?oid=311&aid=0000493101|title='SM\ud0c0\uc6b4' \uacf5\uc5f0\uc2e4\ud669 \ub2e4\ud050, 8\uc6d413\uc77c \uad6d\ub0b4\uac1c\ubd09 \ud655\uc815|publisher=Xports News|date=July 9, 2015|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2019\n| ''Memories of a Dead End''\n| Yumi\n| Lead role \n| <ref name=memories /> \n|-\n| ''[[Girl Cops]]''\n| Jang-mi \n| Supporting role\n| <ref name=girl /> \n|-\n| ''A Little Princess''\n| Adult Gongju \n| Special appearance\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=241&aid=0002985242|title='\uac10\ucabd\uac19\uc740 \uadf8\ub140' \ucd5c\uc218\uc601, \uac10\ucabd\uac19\uc740 \ud2b9\ubcc4\ucd9c\uc5f0..\uac10\ub3c5 \"\uc804\uccb4\ub97c \ud574\uc11d\ud558\ub294 \ubc30\uc6b0\"|publisher=\uc77c\uac04\uc2a4\ud3ec\uce20|date=December 4, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Television series===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Network\n! Role\n! Notes\n! Ref. \n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Unstoppable Marriage (TV series)|Unstoppable Marriage]]''\n| [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]]\n| Choi Soo-young\n| Supporting role\n| <ref name=marriage /> \n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Oh! My Lady]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]\n| Herself\n| Guest appearance; episode 7\n| <ref name=lady /> \n|-\n| 2011\n | ''[[Paradise Ranch]]''\n| Miss Soo\n| Guest appearance; episode 3\n| <ref name=paradise /> \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2012\n| ''[[A Gentleman's Dignity]]''\n| Herself\n| Guest appearance; episode 5\n|<ref name=gentleman>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2954078|title=Sooyoung has TV role as K-pop star|date=June 8, 2012|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Third Hospital]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]]\n| Lee Eui-jin\n| rowspan=\"8\" | Lead role\n|<ref name=hospital /> \n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Dating Agency: Cyrano]]''\n| Gong Min-young\n| <ref name=dating /> \n|-\n| 2014\n | ''[[My Spring Days]]''\n| [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n| Lee Bom-yi\n|<ref name=spring /> \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2016\n| ''Perfect Sense''\n| [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]] \n| Jung Ah-yeon\t\n|<ref name=perfect /> \n|-\n|''[[Squad 38]]''\n| [[Orion Cinema Network|OCN]]\n| Cheon Sung-hee\n|<ref name=ocn /> \n|- \n| 2017\u20132018\n|''[[Man in the Kitchen]]''\n| [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n| Lee Roo-ri\n|<ref name=kitchen />\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Tell Me What You Saw]]''\n| [[Orion Cinema Network|OCN]]\n| Cha Soo-young\n| \n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[So I Married an Anti-fan (TV series)|So I Married an Anti-fan]]''\n| \n| Lee Geun-young\n|<ref name=anti /> \n|}\n\n===Web series===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Network\n! Role\n! Notes\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Someone You Might Know''\n| [[JTBC]]\n| Lee Ahn\n| Lead role\n| <ref name=someone />\n|}\n\n===Variety show===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Network\n! Role\n! Ref. \n|-\n| 2012\u20132014\n| ''TV Entertainment Tonight''\n| [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]\n| Presenter\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/11002|title=Girls' Generation's Sooyoung, YB band's Yoon Do-hyun named new hosts of entertainment news program|date=May 31, 2012|website=10Asia}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Saturday Night Live Korea]]''\n| [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]]\n| Host; season 9\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201703171519428159807_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title='SNL Korea' to kick off ninth season with Sooyoung as host|date=March 17, 2017|publisher=Kpop Herald}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Born 1990 Choi Soo-young''\n| Dingo Studio\n| Host\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvreport.co.kr/?c=news&m=newsview&idx=1032061|title=\"90\ub144\uc0dd \ucd5c\uc218\uc601\uc758 \ubbfc\ub0af\"\u2026\uc218\uc601, \uccab \ub9ac\uc5bc\ub9ac\ud2f0 \ucd9c\uaca9|date=January 11, 2018|website=TV Report|language=ko}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{seealso|List of awards and nominations received by Girls' Generation}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Work !! Result !! Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2012\n| [[Mnet 20's Choice Awards]]\n| Best 20's Style \n| {{NA}}\n| {{nom}}\n| \n|-\n| KBS Music Awards\n| Best Female Group Member\n| {{NA}}\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2013\n| [[6th Korea Drama Awards]]\n| Best New Actress \n| ''[[Dating Agency: Cyrano]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| \n|-\n| 6th [[Style Icon Awards]]\n| Best K-Style Award\n| {{NA}} \n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=213&aid=0000392900|title='2013 SIA' \uc218\uc601-\ucd5c\uc9c4\ud601, '\ubca0\uc2a4\ud2b8 \ucf00\uc774 \uc2a4\ud0c0\uc77c' \ub3d9\ubc18 \uc218\uc0c1|language=Korean|publisher=TV Report|date=October 24, 2013|accessdate=November 20, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[SBS Entertainment Awards]]\n| New Rookie Award (MC Category)\n| ''TV Entertainment Tonight''\n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=011&aid=0002445936|title=SBS \uc5f0\uc608\ub300\uc0c1 '\uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1' \uc218\uc601, \uc218\uc0c1 \uc778\uc99d\uc0f7 \"\uc601\uad11\uc758 \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1\"|publisher=Hankooki|date=December 31, 2013|accessdate=May 28, 2015|language=Korean}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2014\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[2014 MBC Drama Awards|MBC Drama Awards]]\n| Excellence Award, Actress in a Miniseries \n| rowspan=\"3\"|''[[My Spring Days]]''\n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2014123100223539274&outlink=2&SVEC|title=\ud0dc\uc5f0\u00b7\uc368\ub2c8, \uc218\uc601 MBC\uc5f0\uae30\ub300\uc0c1 \uc6b0\uc218 \uc5f0\uae30\uc0c1 \ucd95\ud558|language=Korean|publisher=Star News|date=December 31, 2014|accessdate=May 28, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Couple Award\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imbc.com/broad/tv/ent/event/2014mbc/couple/index.html|title=2014 MBC Drama Award Nominees for \"Best Couple\"|language=Korean|date=December 2014|accessdate=May 28, 2015|publisher=MBC}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015 \n| [[8th Korea Drama Awards]] \n| Excellence Award, Actress \n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=koreanaward2015>{{cite news|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2015090909282924799|title=\uae40\uc218\ud604vs\uc8fc\uc6d0, 2015 \ucf54\ub9ac\uc544\ub4dc\ub77c\ub9c8\uc5b4\uc6cc\uc988 \ub300\uc0c1 \uaca9\ub3cc|language=Korean|publisher=Star News|date=September 9, 2015|accessdate=September 18, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017 \n| [[2017 MBC Drama Awards]] \n| Excellence Award, Actress \n|''[[Man in the Kitchen]]''\n| {{nominated}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2019 \n| 15th [[Jecheon International Music & Film Festival]] \n| Discovery of the Year Award \n|''Memories of a Dead End''\n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/1344500wpp/exos-suho-and-girls-generations-sooyoung-receive-jimff-awards|title=EXO\u2019s Suho And Girls\u2019 Generation\u2019s Sooyoung Receive JIMFF Awards|publisher=Soompi|date=August 9, 2019|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[40th Blue Dragon Film Awards]] \n| Best New Actress\n|''[[Miss & Mrs. Cops]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=076&aid=0003499598 |title=[\uc81c40\ud68c \uccad\ub8e1\uc601\ud654\uc0c1]'\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9' \ub3c5\uc8fcvs\ubc18\uc804\uc758 \uacb0\uacfc'\u2026\uccad\ub8e1D-day, \ud6c4\ubcf4\ubcc4 \uad00\uc804 \ud3ec\uc778\ud2b8 |date=November 21, 2019 |work=Sports Chosun |author=\uc774\uc2b9\ubbf8  |language=Korean}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--per [[WP:EL]], ONE official website is allowed. Pick one and that's it. This is not an SNS directory.-->\n{{Commons category|Choi Soo-young}}\n* {{IMDB person|id=3210659}}\n* {{HanCinema person}}\n\n{{Girls' Generation}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Choi, Soo-young}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gyeonggi Province]]\n[[Category:Girls' Generation members]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language singers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:South Korean female idols]]\n[[Category:South Korean female pop singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:South Korean film actresses]]\n[[Category:South Korean television actresses]]\n[[Category:South Korean television presenters]]\n[[Category:Chung-Ang University alumni]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from South Korea]]\n[[Category:Mandarin-language singers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:21st-century South Korean actresses]]\n", "name_user": "GreekStudMuffin", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Choi_Soo-young"}
{"title_page": "Juan Ponce Enrile", "text_new": "{{about|the Philippine senator|his son|Jack Enrile|the town|Enrile, Cagayan}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Juan Ponce Enrile\n| image               = Juan Ponce Enrile - 2017 (cropped).jpg\n| office              = [[Minority Floor Leader of the Senate of the Philippines|Senate Minority Leader]]\n| term_start          = July 22, 2013\n| term_end            = June 30, 2016\n| predecessor         = [[Alan Peter Cayetano]]\n| successor           = [[Tito Sotto]] ''(acting)''\n| order2              = \n| office2             = [[Senate of the Philippines|Senator of the Philippines]]\n| term_start2         = June 30, 2004\n| term_end2           = June 30, 2016\n| order3              = \n| term_start3         = June 30, 1995\n| term_end3           = June 30, 2001\n| order4              = \n| term_start4         = August 15, 1987\n| term_end4           = June 30, 1992\n| order5              = [[President of the Senate of the Philippines#List of Senate Presidents|26th]]\n| office5             = President of the Senate of the Philippines\n| term_start5         = November 17, 2008\n| term_end5           = June 5, 2013\n| president5          = [[Gloria Macapagal Arroyo]]<br />[[Benigno Aquino III]]\n| predecessor5        = [[Manuel Villar|Manny Villar]]\n| successor5          = [[Franklin Drilon]]\n| order6              = \n| office6             = Member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]] from [[Cagayan]]'s [[Legislative districts of Cagayan#1st District|1st District]]\n| term_start6         = June 30, 1992\n| term_end6           = June 30, 1995\n| predecessor6        = Domingo A. Tuazon\n| successor6          = Patricio T. Antonio\n| office7             = [[Regular Batasang Pambansa|Mambabatas Pambansa (Assemblyman)]] from [[Cagayan]]\n| term_start7         = June 30, 1984\n| term_end7           = March 25, 1986<br />Served with:<br />Antonio C. Carag<br />Alfonso R. Reyno Jr.\n| office8             = [[Interim Batasang Pambansa|Mambabatas Pambansa (Assemblyman)]] from [[Cagayan Valley|Region II]]\n| term_start8         = June 12, 1978\n| term_end8           = June 5, 1984\n| order9              = \n| office9             = [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Minister of National Defense]]\n| term_start9         = January 4, 1972\n| term_end9           = November 23, 1986\n| president9          = [[Ferdinand Marcos]] <br /> [[Corazon Aquino]]\n| predecessor9        = Ferdinand Marcos\n| successor9          = [[Rafael Ileto]]\n| term_start10        = February 9, 1970\n| term_end10          = August 27, 1971\n| president10         = Ferdinand Marcos\n| predecessor10       = Ernesto Mata\n| successor10         = Ferdinand Marcos\n| order11             = \n| office11            = [[Department of Justice (Philippines)|Secretary of Justice]]\n| term_start11        = December 17, 1968\n| term_end11          = February 7, 1970\n| president11         = Ferdinand Marcos\n| predecessor11       = [[Claudio Teehankee|Claudio Teehankee Sr.]]\n| successor11         = Felix Makasiar\n| order12             = \n| office12            = [[Department of Finance (Philippines)|Secretary of Finance]] (''acting'')\n| term_start12        = 1966\n| term_end12          = 1968\n| president12         = Ferdinand Marcos\n| predecessor12       = Eduardo Romualdez\n| successor12         = Eduardo Romualdez\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1924|2|14}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Resume of Senator Enrile |url=http://www.senate.gov.ph/senators/sen_bio/enrile_resume.asp |website=Senate of the Philippines: 18th Congress |publisher=Senate of the Philippines |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n| birthplace         = [[Gonzaga, Cagayan|Gonzaga]], [[Cagayan]], [[Insular Government of the Philippine Islands|Philippine Islands]]\n| birth_name          = Juan Furagganan Ponce Enrile<ref>{{Philippine name|Furagganan|ph=natural}}</ref>\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = [[Filipino people|Filipino]]\n| party               = [[United Nationalist Alliance|UNA]] (2012\u2013present)\n| otherparty          = [[Nacionalista Party|Nacionalista]] (1965\u20131972; 1987\u20131995)<br />[[Kilusang Bagong Lipunan|KBL]] (1978\u20131986) <br /> [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal]] (1995\u20132001) <br /> [[Puwersa ng Masang Pilipino|PMP]] (2001\u20132012)\n| spouse              = Cristina Casta\u00f1er\n| relations           = \n| children            = [[Jack Enrile|Juan Ponce Enrile Jr.]]<br /> Katrina Ponce Enrile\n| residence           = [[Gonzaga, Cagayan]]<br />[[Dasmari\u00f1as Village]], [[Makati City]], [[Metro Manila]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Ateneo de Manila University]]<br />[[University of the Philippines College of Law]]<br />[[Harvard Law School]]\n| occupation          = [[Lawyer]]<br />Ponce Enrile, Reyes & Manalastas (1983\u20132020)\n| profession          = [[Politician]]\n| languages           = [[Ilocano language|Ilocano]], [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]], [[Ibanag language|Ibanag]], [[English language in the Philippines|English]]\n| religion            = [[Catholic Church in the Philippines|Roman Catholic]] <br /> <small> ''formerly'' [[Iglesia Filipina Independiente|Aglipayan]] </small>\n| signature           = \n| website             = \n| footnotes           = \n| caption             = Enrile in 2017\n}}\n\n'''Juan Furagganan Ponce Enrile Sr.''' ({{IPA-tl|hw\u0250\u031en \u02c8p\u0254\u031dns\u025b\u031d \u025bn\u02c8ril\u025b|lang}}; born February 14, 1924), abbreviated '''JPE''', is a [[Filipino people|Filipino]] [[politician]] and [[lawyer]]. He was a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[President of the Philippines|President]] [[Ferdinand Marcos]], and served as [[Department of Justice (Philippines)|Justice Secretary]] and [[Secretary of National Defense (Philippines)|Defense Minister]] under the [[History of the Philippines (1965-1986)|Marcos regime]]. He later became one of the leaders (along with General [[Fidel Ramos]]) of the [[People Power Revolution|1986 People Power Revolution]] that drove Marcos from power and into exile. Enrile has continued to be a prominent politician since then; he was [[Senate of the Philippines|Senate President]] from November 2008 until his resignation on June 5, 2013.\n\n==Early life and career==\nEnrile was born in [[Gonzaga, Cagayan]] to Petra Furagganan, the stepdaughter of a poor fisherman. He was born out of wedlock\u2014his Spanish ''mestizo'' father was the powerful regional politician and renowned lawyer Alfonso Ponce Enrile, who was already married. His second great-uncle was [[Mariano Ponce]]. As a young man, he was reunited with his father in the [[City of Manila]], and took his secondary education at [[St. James Academy (Malabon)|Saint James Academy]] in [[Malabon]].\n\nHe graduated [[Latin honors|''cum laude'']] in 1949 with an [[Associate of Arts]] degree from [[Ateneo de Manila University]]. Afterward, he attended the [[University of the Philippines]] [[University of the Philippines College of Law|College of Law]] and graduated ''cum laude'' with a [[Bachelor of Laws]] degree.  While in law school, he joined the Sigma Rho fraternity. Upon graduation, he was elected to the [[Pi Gamma Mu]] and [[Phi Kappa Phi]] international honor societies. He scored 11th in the 1953 [[Philippine Bar Examination|bar examinations]] with a 91.72% rating and a perfect score in mercantile law. As a scholar at the [[Harvard Law School]], he earned a [[Master of Laws]] degree with specialized training in international tax law.\n\nHe taught law at the [[Far Eastern University]] and practiced law in his father's law firm before taking responsibility for then Senator [[Ferdinand Marcos]]'s personal legal affairs in 1964, especially during the latter's term as Senate President.  After Marcos was elected president in 1965, Enrile became part of his inner circle. From 1966 to 1968, he was the Undersecretary and sometime Acting Secretary of the Department of Finance. He concurrently became acting Insurance Commissioner and Commissioner of the Bureau of Customs. From 1968 to 1970, he was the Secretary of Justice.\n\n==Career in the Marcos Cabinet==\n[[File:Marcos in Washington 1983.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Minister of National Defense Juan Ponce Enrile with President [[Ferdinand Marcos]].]]\n\nEnrile, like Marcos, comes from the northern Philippines, a region that had become Marcos' recruiting ground for key political and military leaders during his time. Enrile was with Marcos since his election in 1965.<ref name=\"ERF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1986/02/22/Enrile-and-Ramos-Former-loyalists-turn-on-Marcos/1656509432400/|title=Enrile and Ramos: Former loyalists turn on Marcos|publisher=}}</ref> His campaign efforts were rewarded with an appointment as chief of the Customs Bureau and the government's insurance commission.\n\nThe [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Department of National Defense]] would expand its power when Marcos assumed the presidency in 1965. Marcos appointed Enrile as his Secretary of National Defense on February 9, 1970, a position Enrile held until August 27, 1971, when he resigned to run unsuccessfully for the senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.ph/history-the-department-of-national-defense/|title=History: The Department of National Defense|publisher=}}</ref> He was re-appointed Defense Secretary by Marcos on January 4, 1972. As Defense Secretary, he was the highest ranked commissioned officer of a nation's armed forces.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\nFrom the beginning of Marcos' period in government, Enrile was one of the few that the former president trusted, and was seen by many as Marcos' prot\u00e9g\u00e9. For almost the entire period of [[Martial law in the Philippines|Martial Law]], Enrile served officially as the martial law administrator as he was in charge of all the armed forces' services during that time. Furthermore, as early as Marcos' planning and preparation for the declaration of martial law, Enrile was involved.<ref>[http://www.manilatimes.net/why-not-ask-ramos-and-enrile-about-martial-law-abuses/247486/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811031757/https://www.manilatimes.net/why-not-ask-ramos-and-enrile-about-martial-law-abuses/247486/ |date=August 11, 2018 }} Why Not Ask Ramos and Enrile About Martial Law Abuses</ref> In his memoir, Enrile recalls Marcos' careful preparations. He narrates that as early as December 1969, Marcos instructed him to study the 1935 Constitution, specifically the powers of the President as Commander-in-Chief. Marcos had already foreseen a rise in violence and chaos in the country and wanted to know the exact extent of his powers.<ref name=\"DML\" />\n                  \t\nAt the end of January of the following year, Enrile, with help from Efren Plana and Minerva Gonzaga Reyes, submitted the only copy of the report regarding the detailed nature and extent of Martial Law to Marcos. Soon after, Marcos allegedly ordered Enrile to prepare all documents necessary for the implementation of [[Martial Law in the Philippines]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16055240-juan-ponce-enrile | title=Juan Ponce Enrile, A Memoir | publisher=[[ABS-CBN Publishing]] | author=Juan Ponce Enrile | year=2012 | isbn=\n978-9-7181-6117-3 | editor=Navarro, Nelson A. }}</ref> In August 1972, Marcos once again met with Enrile and a few of his other most trusted commanders to discuss tentative dates for the declaration. By September 22, 1972, Marcos announced that he had placed the entire country under Martial Law as of 9 p.m. via proclamation 1081 which, he claimed, he had signed on September 21, 1972.<ref name=\"DML\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gov.ph/featured/declaration-of-martial-law/ | title=Declaration of Martial Law | work=[[Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines]] | accessdate= | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927014532/https://www.gov.ph/featured/declaration-of-martial-law/ | archivedate= September 27, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n[[File:Marcos Declares Martial Law.jpg|thumb|left|\"FM Declares Martial Law\"\u2014the headline of the September 24, 1972 issue of the ''Sunday Express'', which was the Sunday edition of the ''[[Philippines Daily Express]]''. The ''Daily Express'' was the only newspaper allowed to circulate upon the declaration of Martial Law.]]\n\nOne of Marcos' justifications for the declaration of martial law that year was terrorism. He cited the alleged ambush attack on Enrile's car on September 22, 1972 as pretext for martial law. At the time, many people doubted that the attack actually took place. Marcos, in his diary entry for September 1972, wrote that Enrile had been ambushed near Wack-Wack that night. He says \"it was a good thing he was riding in his security car as a protective measure\u2026 This makes the martial law proclamation a necessity.\"<ref name=\"DML\" /> On the contrary, Oscar Lopez, a resident of Wack-Wack who lived along the street of the alleged ambush, stated that he had heard a lot of shooting on the night of the incident. When he went out to see what was happening, he saw only an empty car riddled with bullets. Lopez' driver, who had happened to witness the incident, stated that \"there was a car that came and stopped beside a Meralco post. Some people exited the car, and another car came by to shoot at the car, to make it look like it was ambushed.\"<ref name=\"DML\" />\n\n[[File:Juan Ponce Enrile's Bullet-riddled car.jpg|thumb|left|Juan Ponce Enrile's bullet-riddled car]]\n \nThe doubts surrounding the alleged ambush were further confirmed in a press conference on February 23, 1986 when then Lieutenant General Fidel Ramos and Enrile admitted that the attack was staged in order to justify the declaration of martial law. Both radio and television media covered this and millions of Filipinos witnessed the said confession. Furthermore, in several interviews, Enrile was reported as indeed confirming that the attempted assassination was faked in order to justify the declaration of Martial Law.<ref name=\"ERF\" /><ref name=\"Inquirer\" >{{cite web | url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/284836/true-or-false-was-1972-enrile-ambush-faked#ixzz4QFSz3iDu | title=True or false: Was 1972 Enrile ambush faked? | work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] | date=October 8, 2012 | accessdate=December 23, 2019 | author=Inquirer Research}}</ref> Conflicting accounts arise in his book, ''Juan Ponce Enrile: A Memoir''. In the said book, Enrile accuses his political opponents of spreading rumors of the ambush being staged despite having already admitted several times that the attempted assassination was indeed fake.<ref name=\"Memoir review\">{{cite web | url=https://book2luv.blogspot.com/2018/03/juan-ponce-enrile-memoir_25.html | title=Juan Ponce Enrile, A Memoir | work=The Book Lover blog | date=March 25, 2018 | accessdate=December 19, 2019 | author=Aenlle, Mike }}</ref><ref name=\"Inquirer\" />\n\nDespite later controversy, at the time, Enrile remained one of Marcos' most loyal allies. In 1973, under the new modified [[parliamentary system]] then in place under the country's new constitution under Martial Law, Enrile's title became Defense Minister. Enrile focused his efforts on a broad review of defense policies and on dealing with pressing social unrest. The abolition of civilian institutions such as [[Congress of the Philippines|Congress]], the weakening of the judiciary, and the outlawing of [[Political party|political parties]], left the military as the only other instrumentality of the national government outside of the Presidency.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\nAccording to the [[National Historical Institute of the Philippines]], Enrile was also appointed as the general for logging in the Philippines. He was tasked by Marcos to give certificates to logging companies, which eventually led to one of Asia's most devastating environmental disasters. During that time, the forest cover of the Philippines shrank until only 8% remained. Enrile also owned numerous logging companies such as Ameco in Bukidnon, Dolores Timber in Samar, San Jose Timber in Northern Samar, Kasilagan Softwood Development Corp in Butuan, Eurasia Match in Cebu, Pan Oriental which operates in Cebu and Butuan, Palawan-Apitong Corp in Palawan, and Royal Match. He also invested heavily in a rubber plantation in Basilan. A share of the Marcos ill-gotten wealth was siphoned in those companies. Enrile was also appointed by Marcos as the President of the [[Philippine Coconut Authority]], where he established control of the copra industry together with Danding Cojuangco. The two ruled over the controversial Coco Levy Fund which proved their intense corruption in government service. The fund, which was supposed to be used to improve the country's copra industry, was used by the two for programs led by Imelda Marcos and other [[Marcos cronies]]. A huge portion of the fund was also used for the presidential campaigns of Ferdinand Marcos in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5reVY2X8PS0|title=EP09 KAYO ANG HIHIRAP KAMI ANG YAYAMAN|publisher=[[National Historical Commission of the Philippines]]|date=September 20, 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nOn November 28, 1978, Marcos issued the Letter of Instruction no. 776, which stated that \"No changes of assignment of senior officers including provincial commanders, brigade commanders, division commanders, and special unit commanders shall be made without clearance from the president.\"<ref>[http://www.gov.ph/1978/11/28/letter-of-instruction-no-776-s-1978/] Letter of Instruction No. 776</ref> By the 1980s, Marcos began to bypass Enrile's authority. He clipped the powers of the Minister of National Defense and the Chief of Staff over the Armed Forces of the Philippines.<ref name=\"Seesaw Life\">{{cite web | url=http://www.philstar.com/opinion/2015/09/09/1497632/seesaw-life-juan-ponce-enrile | title=The Seesaw Life of Juan Ponce Enrile | work=[[The Philippine Star]] | date=September 8, 2015 | accessdate=December 23, 2019 | author=Katigbak, Tony }}</ref>\n\nAfter opposition leader Senator [[Benigno Aquino, Jr.|Benigno \"Ninoy\" Aquino, Jr.]] was [[Assassination of Benigno Aquino, Jr.|assassinated on August 21, 1983]], Enrile started to break away from the increasingly unpopular Marcos dictatorship. He began aligning himself with dissident elements in the army, particularly the [[Reform the Armed Forces Movement]] - which was then headed by his [[Aide-de-camp]], Lieutenant Colonel Gregorio Honasan. On February 15, 1986, Aquino's wife, [[Cory Aquino]], gained mass support through her oath taking in protest of Marcos being announced president. This then led to many leaders joining the revolution and fight against Marcos.<ref name=\"Tavaana\"/>\n\nOfficers from the group, with Enrile's support, launched a ''[[coup d'\u00e9tat]]'' against Marcos in February 1986. Marcos was alerted to the plot by Ver, and the conspirators took refuge in two military camps. From there, Enrile and then Lieutenant General [[Fidel Ramos]], the head of the defunct [[Philippine Constabulary]] (it had been integrated with the INP to form the [[Philippine National Police]]) and concurrently vice-chief of staff of the armed forces, rallied opponents against Marcos in a citizens' revolt that became known as the [[People Power Revolution]]. They called on the people to gather in Epifanio de los Santos Avenue ([[EDSA (road)|EDSA]]) to support on February 22. The next three days, they continued their rally in EDSA now containing two million people in support. The growing number encouraged many more leaders to support the movement against Marcos. Enrile stated, \"It was funny.\u2026 We in the defense and military organizations who should be protecting the people were being protected by them.\"<ref name=\"Tavaana\">{{cite web | url=https://tavaana.org/en/en/content/people-power-revolution-philippines-i-saw-no-one-yield-fear | title=People Power Revolution Philippines: I Saw No One Yield | publisher=Tavaana | accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career in the Aquino Cabinet==\nEnrile then served as the Secretary of National Defense under Corazon Aquino, who had replaced Marcos as president, but he increasingly differed with Aquino, specifically on the administration's handling of insurgent leftist opposition. Aquino sought to make peace with the communist party of the Philippines through the use and promotions of ceasefires during which peace talks were to be held between the government and the leftist opposition. Because of such tactics, Enrile was not the only person dissatisfied with Aquino administration. Many of the younger officers in the military who had been identified as members of the Reform the Armed Forces Movement and Marcos loyalists sought to oust Aquino from the presidency with the many coups that were plotted from 1986 to 1990. The earliest and most prominent one was the [[1986-1990 Philippine coup attempts|\"God Save the Queen\" plot]] that was to supposedly be executed on the November 11, 1986.<ref>[http://www.gov.ph/1990/10/03/the-final-report-of-the-fact-finding-commission-ii-political-change-and-military-transmition-in-the-philippines-1966-1989-from-the-barracks-to-the-corridors-of-power/] Final Report of the Fact Finding Commission</ref> The investigation of the coup done by the Fact Finding Commission found that Enrile and some members of the RAM as the primary instigators of the coup. After revealing the fruits of the investigation findings, Aquino forced Enrile to resign as Defense Secretary in November 1986 as she had lost confidence in him. Enrile was then replaced with [[Rafael Ileto]].\n\n==Congressional career==\n\n===First Senate term===\nIn May 1987 Enrile won a seat in the [[1987 Philippine Senate election|1987 election]] as one of two opposition members in the country's 24-member [[Senate of the Philippines|Senate]] (the other being [[Joseph Estrada]]), finishing 24th. He was unable to be proclaimed until August, when the electoral protest filed by Augusto Sanchez was dismissed. He formally assumed office on August 15, 1987. In the same month, an [[1986\u20131987 Philippine coup attempts|attempted coup against Aquino]] escalated and led to the destruction of the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines|Armed Forces]] General Headquarters (AFPGHQ) in [[Camp Aguinaldo]] in [[Quezon City]]. He was detained in Camp Aguinaldo over suspicion of planning the coup with Lt. Col. [[Gregorio Honasan]], but was released days later for lack of evidence. Enrile later stated numerous recalls about the martial law era, of which all were flip-flops from his previous statements during his term a secretary of defense and during the ouster of Marcos. He was dubbed by then-President [[Corazon Aquino]] as \"''Pambansang Balimbing''\" (national political turncoat) for his contradicting statements and \"''Dakilang Miron''\" (great bystander) for his inconvenient bystander and opportunistic attitude.<ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6d8JJzuks0Q&t=13s|title=President Corazon Aquino blasts Enrile and coup rebels at EDSA (1990)|first=|last=Maypagasa|date=August 23, 2015|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref name=\"youtube.com\"/>\n\n===Member of the House of Representatives===\nIn 1992, before his term in the Senate had ended, Enrile predicted that he might lose the senatorial election or win, but only serve three years in office. Under the transitory provisions of the [[Philippine Constitution|1987 Constitution]], the 12 candidates who receive the greatest number of votes serve a six-year term, the next 12 only three years. He ran instead for the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines]]. He [[1992 Philippine House of Representatives elections|was elected]] and represented the First District of [[Cagayan]].\n\n===Second to fourth senate terms===\nIn 1995 Enrile ran in the senatorial race as an independent candidate for [[Senate of the Philippines|senator]] and was also a guest candidate under the [[Lakas NUCD|Lakas]]&ndash;[[Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino|Laban]] coalition. He [[1995 Philippine Senate election|won as senator]] and held the position until 2001. During his term as senator, he ran as an independent candidate in the [[1998 Philippine presidential election|1998 election]] for the position of [[President of the Philippines|President]]. He lost to then [[Vice President of the Philippines|Vice President]] Joseph Estrada.\n\nOn January 13, 2001 he was one of those who voted against the opening of the second bank envelope.{{clarify|date=September 2011}} That vote led to the [[EDSA II|second EDSA People Power Revolution]] that eventually ousted President Estrada. From April 30 to May 1, 2001, together with [[Miriam Defensor Santiago]], [[Gregorio Honasan]], [[Panfilo Lacson]] and [[Vicente Sotto III]], he led the [[EDSA III]] protests in support of [[Joseph Estrada]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/90521/miriam-gma-resign-or-we-will-storm-palace|title= Miriam to GMA: Resign or we will storm palace\n|newspaper=[[Philippine Star]]|date=April 30, 2001|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"EDSA INC\" />  May 1, 2001, the protesters stormed [[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace]].<ref name=\"EDSA INC\" >{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/in-depth/104045-edsa-3-iglesia-ni-cristo|title= Remembering the Iglesia-led EDSA 3\n|work=[[Rappler]]|date=August 25, 2015|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref> In May 2001 he was indicted by the military for the investigation of the unsuccessful siege of the [[Malaca\u00f1an Palace]] by pro-Estrada forces. He was released a day later. He ran for [[2001 Philippine Senate election|reelection]] as part of the [[Puwersa ng Masa]] coalition. Due to the issues that haunted him over the failed siege, he lost the election.\n\nIn the [[2004 Philippine Senate election|2004 election]], he made a comeback bid for the Senate under the [[Koalisyon ng Nagkakaisang Pilipino]] (KNP) banner. He actively opposed the imposition of the Purchased Power Adjustment (PPA) on consumers' electric bills. Due to his expos\u00e9 of the PPA and the [[Supreme Court of the Philippines|Supreme Court]] decision in favour of a refund on electric bills, the public responded positively and elected him. He thus became a senator in three non-consecutive terms. He was reelected as senator in the [[2010 Philippine Senate election|2010 election]]s. {{asof|2013}}, he is the oldest senator of the [[15th Congress of the Philippines]]. Enrile is affiliated with the [[Pwersa ng Masang Pilipino]] (PMP). Technically he belongs to an opposition party, but in the Senate, he stands as an independent and is part of the administration bloc. The minority bloc includes all of his party's members.\n\n==Senate Presidency==\n\n===Election===\nOn November 17, 2008, Senate President [[Manuel Villar]] resigned due to lack of support, and Enrile succeeded him the same day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.easybourse.com/bourse-actualite/marches/senators-name-juan-ponce-enrile-as-new-philippine-senate-562997|title=easybourse.com, Senators Name Juan Ponce Enrile As New Philippine Senate President|access-date=November 17, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221140806/http://www.easybourse.com/bourse-actualite/marches/senators-name-juan-ponce-enrile-as-new-philippine-senate-562997|archive-date=December 21, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=ABS>{{cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/11/17/08/enrile-ousts-villar-senate-coup|title=(Update) Enrile ousts Villar in Senate coup|first=ABS-CBN|last=News|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-11/17/content_10371979.htm news.xinhuanet.com, Philippine senate president resigns] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221153448/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-11/17/content_10371979.htm |date=December 21, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/133995/Zubiri-is-new-Senate-Majority-Leader|title=Zubiri is new Senate Majority Leader|publisher=}}</ref> Enrile was nominated by [[Panfilo Lacson]]; 14 senators supported the nomination and five abstained.<ref name=ABS/> Enrile accepted the position, saying that \"To lead the Senate with its great minds, strong advocacies, varying and independent political beliefs and leanings, is not an easy task. But it is precisely this variance in points of view and the battle of great ideas that provide the dynamism we need to craft legislation that takes into account and balances the competing interests involved \u2013 with the end in view of serving the greater good of the people to whom we owe our mandate.\"{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n\n===Legislation===\nUnder his leadership, the Senate passed vital pieces of legislation such as the CARP Extension, Anti-Torture Act, Expanded Senior Citizens Act, Anti-Child Pornography Act, National Heritage Conservation Act, Real Estate Investment Act, among many others. Institutional reforms were also implemented within the Senate to improve the daily conduct of business as well the welfare of its officers and employees.\n\n===Maguindanao martial law===\nThe Senate also collaborated with the House of Representatives on two crucial issues which are now considered historical milestones. In December 2009, it used Proclamation No. 1959 of the previous administration, declaring a state of martial law and suspending the privilege of the writ of ''[[habeas corpus]]'' in the province of Maguindanao, while in May 2010, Congress convened to constitute itself as the national board to canvass the votes for president and vice president, and proclaim the winners.\n\n===Re-election as Senate President===\n[[File:Hajime Ishii and Juan Ponce Enrile 20110504.jpg|thumb|200px|with [[Hajime Ishii]] (left) on May 4, 2011]]\n\nEnrile was re-elected to a fourth term in the [[2010 Philippine Senate election|2010 Senate election]]. On July 26, 2010, he was re-elected President of the Senate. Enrile committed himself to \"discharge my duties and responsibilities with honor, with total devotion to our institution, and with fairness to all members. No partisan consideration will blur or color the treatment of any member of the Senate. We are all Senators elected by the people to serve them with dedication to their interest and well-being and devotion to our responsibilities.\" Furthermore, in his acceptance speech, he enjoined his colleagues to \"uphold the independence and integrity of this Senate, without abandoning our duty to cooperate with the other departments of the government to achieve what is good for our people.\"<ref>[https://www.senate.gov.ph/senators/senpres/enrile.asp] Biography of Senate Presidents - Juan Ponce Enrile. Retrieved November 29, 2016</ref>\n\n===Corona's impeachment, various feuds, and controversies===\nIn early 2012 Enrile was the presiding officer of the [[Impeachment of Renato Corona|Impeachment of Chief Justice Renato Corona]]. He was one of the 20 Senators voting guilty for the impeachment. In September 2012 he started a feud with [[Antonio Trillanes IV]] when he asked Trillanes why he secretly visited [[Beijing]] to talk about the [[Philippines and the Spratly Islands]] dispute on [[Spratlys]] and the [[Scarborough Shoal]]. Trillanes said his visit in China was authorized by the [[Malaca\u00f1an|Palace]]. He also alleged that Enrile was being pushed by former Pres. [[Gloria Arroyo]] to pass a bill splitting the province of [[Camarines Sur]] into two but Enrile denied the allegation.\n\nIn late 2012, Enrile also started a feud with [[Miriam Defensor Santiago]] when Santiago authored the [[Responsible Parenthood and Reproductive Health Act of 2012]] with [[Pia Cayetano]], which he opposed. In January 2013, Santiago exposed that Enrile allegedly gave PhP 1.6 million each to his fellow Senators, except for her, [[Pia Cayetano]], [[Alan Peter Cayetano]], and Trillanes, who were reportedly to have been only given PhP 250 thousand each. He admitted giving the said amount to the senators, saying it was part of the balance of the maintenance and other operating expenses (MOOE) funds allowed per senator. On January 21, 2013, because of the controversies involving him, he attempted to vacate his position as Senate President but his motion was rejected.\n\n===Resignation===\nAmid accusations against him, including the alleged distribution of MOOE funds to senators, Enrile stepped down as Senate President after his privilege speech on June 5, 2013.<ref>[http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/311510/news/nation/enrile-resigns-as-senate-president Enrile resigns as Senate president] retrieved June 5, 2013</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n\n===Enrile cash gift===\nIn January 2013, while sitting as the Senate President, Enrile was accused of using Senate funds called MOOE as Christmas gifts to members of the senate who do not oppose him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/19395-enrile-s-cash-gifts-exclude-4-critics|title=Enrile's 'cash gifts' exclude 4 critics|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/337461/enrile-gave-18-senators-p1-6m-each-for-christmas|title=Enrile gave 18 senators P1.6M each for Christmas|first=Juliet|last=Labog-Javellana|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/289408/news/nation/enrile-gave-p1-6m-to-all-fellow-senators-except-his-foes|title=Enrile gave P1.6M to all fellow senators except his foes|publisher=}}</ref> This led to his resignation as Senate President without sufficiently answering the controversy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/421361/enrile-quits-slams-critics|title=Enrile quits, slams critics|first=Cathy|last=Yamsuan|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Pork barrel scam===\n{{main|Priority Development Assistance Fund scam}}\n[[File:Bong Revilla after delivering \"Salamat, Kaibigan\".jpg|thumb|200px|Enrile with Senators [[Jinggoy Estrada]] (left) and [[Bong Revilla]] (center) after Revilla's Privilege Speech at the Senate floor on June 9, 2014]]\n\nIn September 2013, Enrile was again involved in misappropriated funds, this time with regard to the PDAF or what is commonly called the [[pork barrel]] fund. Twenty billion pesos worth of Priority Development Fund was illegally channeled through various bogus NGOs of Janet Napoles which most of it being used by the Senator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2013/09/14/1208471/luy-napoles-ngos-shifted-pork-lgus-2011|title=Luy: Napoles NGOs shifted \u2018pork\u2019 to LGUs in 2011 - Philstar.com|website=philstar.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/473291/chief-aide-in-charge-of-enriles-pdaf-deals|title=Chief aide in charge of Enrile\u2019s PDAF deals|first=Gil C.|last=Cabacungan|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nEnrile, along with fellow senators [[Bong Revilla]], and [[Jinggoy Estrada]], were indicted for [[plunder]] and for the violation of the Anti-Graft and Corrupt Practices Act before the Sandiganbayan  on June 6, 2014 in connection to the [[Priority Development Assistance Fund scam]]. Alleged mastermind Janet Lim Napoles and Enrile's former chief of staff Gigi Reyes were also charged. Enrile allegedly received \u20b1172 million in kickbacks from public funds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/59826-enrile-jpe-jinggoy-charged-plunder-pdaf-scam|title=3 PH senators charged with plunder over PDAF scam|publisher=}}</ref> He was detained on July 3, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/617113/enrile-in-hospital-arrest-gigi-reyes-at-qc-jail|title=Enrile in hospital arrest; Gigi Reyes at QC jail|first=Dona Z. Pazzibugan, TJ|last=Burgonio|publisher=}}</ref> and suspended from his Senate post<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/634331/senate-carries-out-enrile-suspension|title=Senate carries out Enrile suspension|first=Maila|last=Ager|publisher=}}</ref> on September 1, 2014 for these charges, after his motions to post bail to lift the suspension order were denied.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mb.com.ph/enriles-motion-to-fix-bail-denied |title=Archived copy |access-date=September 3, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905014344/http://www.mb.com.ph/enriles-motion-to-fix-bail-denied/ |archive-date=September 5, 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/08/22/14/sandigan-denies-enriles-plea-not-be-suspended|title=Sandigan denies Enrile's plea not to be suspended|first=ABS-CBN|last=News|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nEnrile, or \"''Manong Johnny''\" as he is often called (''manong'' is an [[Ilokano language|Ilocano]] term of endearment for an older brother), is married to Cristina Casta\u00f1er, a Spaniard, who has served as the Philippine Ambassador to the [[Holy See]]. They have two children: Juan Jr. (Jack) and Katrina. Juan Jr. is currently congressman for the 1st District of [[Cagayan]] and running for a Senate seat under [[United Nationalist Alliance|UNA]], while Katrina is currently CEO of Enrile's company Jaka Group, which owns the Philippine Match Company. Enrile has a half-sister, [[Armida Siguion-Reyna]], who is a singer as well as a theatre and film actress.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Flores|first1=Wilson Lee|title=Armida Siguion-Reyna: The singer, the song, her fight for artistic freedom, her love for Imelda & Kris|url=http://www.philstar.com/sunday-life/2015/02/22/1426174/armida-siguion-reyna-singer-song-her-fight-artistic-freedom-her-love|work=The Philippine Star|date=February 22, 2015|quote=She is also known as the half-sister of former Senate President Juan Ponce Enrile.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ca\u00f1ares-Yamsuan|first1=Cathy|title='Aawitan Kita': In biography, Armida Siguion-Reyna faces the music|url=http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/185284/aawitan-kita-in-biography-armida-siguion-reyna-faces-the-music/|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=February 23, 2015|quote=Navarro, who also edited the self-titled autobiography of Armida's elder brother Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile released in 2012, recalled that Estrada summoned top movie producers for dinner in Malaca\u00f1ang on July 9, 1999.}}</ref>\n\nEnrile's rumored affair with his former long-time employee and chief of staff Jessica Lucila \"Gigi\" Reyes, 38 years his junior, came out after reports that Enrile's wife, Cristina, walked out on him in January 1998 after charging him with adultery. The news made both local and international headlines.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schmetzer|first1=Uli|title=Filipinos Riveted By Their Own News Of High-level Trysts|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-01-30/news/9801300110_1_filipinos-sen-juan-ponce-enrile-president-fidel-ramos|work=Chicago Tribune|date=January 30, 1998}}</ref> Gigi Reyes was regarded as \"the door, if not the bridge\" to Enrile, referring to the extent of closeness between the two. Enrile's special fondness for Reyes was again called out by Sen. [[Alan Peter Cayetano]], after Reyes accused Cayetano in a media interview of hypocrisy for supposedly receiving a \"cash gift\" from Enrile.<ref name=\"rappler.com\">{{cite news|last1=Hofile\u00f1a|first1=Chay|title='The Boss' and Gigi Reyes|url=http://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/40261-boss-enrile-gigi-reyes|work=Rappler|date=October 1, 2013}}</ref> The incident led to Reyes's resignation from Enrile's office, which Reyes said was also for her criticising on how Enrile responded to the issue of fund misuse. Enrile insisted the resignation was because of rumors of their illicit relationship.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Macaraig|first1=Ayee|title=Gigi Reyes packs up from Enrile office|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/20611-gigi-reyes-packs-up-from-enrile-office|work=Rappler|date=January 28, 2013}}</ref> Reyes's name was once again linked to Enrile's name for signing documents that facilitated the release of Enrile's PDAF to fake non-governmental organizations (NGOs) linked to Janet Lim Napoles, the woman who is said to be behind the PDAF scam.<ref name=\"rappler.com\"/>\n\n==Seeking clemency for those convicted of the Aquino assassination==\nOn August 21, 2007, the 24th anniversary of Senator Aquino's death, Enrile stated that the case of the 14 soldiers incarcerated for 24 years for his assassination should be reviewed for clemency. Enrile paid for the legal services of the soldiers during their trial, and said the soldiers and their families had suffered enough. Fifteen soldiers of the Aviation Security Command had been sentenced to double life imprisonment for the double murder of Aquino and his alleged lone communist gunman, [[Rolando Galman]], and one of them had since died. They were all acquitted in December 1985 by the [[Sandiganbayan]]'s Manuel Pamaran, but when the entire proceedings were invalidated by the Supreme Court and the case retried, the Sandiganbayan's Regino C. Hermosisima, Jr. (promoted as [[Supreme Court of the Philippines|Supreme Court Associate Justice]]) convicted them again on September 28, 1990.<ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view_article.php?article_id=83821  Inquirer.net, Enrile seeks clemency for soldiers in Aquino slay] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013123302/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view_article.php?article_id=83821 |date=October 13, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*Portrayed by [[Joonee Gamboa]] in the 1988 TV drama film ''[[A Dangerous Life]]''\n\n*Portrayed by [[Enrique Gil]] in the TV drama anthology series ''[[Maalaala Mo Kaya]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jpenrile.com]\n*[http://www.senate.gov.ph/senators/sen_bio/enrile_bio.asp]\n*[http://www.i-site.ph/Databases/Congress/13thSenate/SALS/enrile-SAL.html Juan Ponce Enrile's Assets and Liabilities]\n*[http://www.senate.gov.ph/senators/sen_bio/enrile_bio.asp  Juan Ponce Enrile's Official Philippine Senate biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box |\n  before= [[Manny Villar]] |\n  title= [[President of the Senate of the Philippines]]&nbsp;|\n  years= November 17, 2008 \u2013 June 5, 2013 |\n  after= [[Jinggoy Estrada]]\n}}\n{{succession box |\n  before= Ernesto Mata <br /> [[Ferdinand Marcos]] |\n  title= [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Philippine Secretary of National Defense]] |\n  years= February 9, 1970 \u2013 August 27, 1971 <br /> January 4, 1972 \u2013 November 23, 1986|\n  after= [[Ferdinand E. Marcos]] <br /> [[Rafael Ileto|Rafael M. Ileto]]\n}}\n{{succession box |\n  before= [[Claudio Teehankee, Sr.]] |\n  title= [[Department of Justice (Philippines)|Philippine Secretary of Justice]] |\n  years= December 17, 1968 \u2013 February 7, 1970 |\n  after= [[Felix Makasiar]] |\n}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Philippine Senate Presidents}}\n{{PhilSenMinLdrz}}\n{{navboxes\n|title=Senatorial history of Juan Ponce Enrile\n|list=\n{{8th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{10th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{11th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{13th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{14th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{15th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{16th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n}}\n{{Candidates in the Philippine presidential election, 1998}}\n{{Martial EDSA}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ponce Enrile, Juan}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ateneo de Manila University alumni]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1998 Philippine presidential election]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:Filipino lawyers]]\n[[Category:Filipino Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Ilocano people]]\n[[Category:Independent politicians in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Kilusang Bagong Lipunan politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Representatives of the Philippines from Cagayan]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Senate of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 16th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 15th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 14th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 13th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 11th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 10th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 8th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Minority leaders of the Senate of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Nacionalista Party politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Cagayan]]\n[[Category:People from Makati]]\n[[Category:People from Marikina]]\n[[Category:Pwersa ng Masang Pilipino politicians]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of National Defense of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of Justice of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of Finance of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Commissioners of the Bureau of Customs of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:University of the Philippines alumni]]\n[[Category:United Nationalist Alliance politicians]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Corazon Aquino Administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:Marcos Administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:Members of the Batasang Pambansa]]\n[[Category:People of the People Power Revolution]]\n[[Category:Filipino people of Spanish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Philippine senator|his son|Jack Enrile|the town|Enrile, Cagayan}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Juan Ponce Enrile\n| image               = Juan Ponce Enrile - 2017 (cropped).jpg\n| office              = [[Minority Floor Leader of the Senate of the Philippines|Senate Minority Leader]]\n| term_start          = July 22, 2013\n| term_end            = June 30, 2016\n| predecessor         = [[Alan Peter Cayetano]]\n| successor           = [[Tito Sotto]] ''(acting)''\n| order2              = \n| office2             = [[Senate of the Philippines|Senator of the Philippines]]\n| term_start2         = June 30, 2004\n| term_end2           = June 30, 2016\n| order3              = \n| term_start3         = June 30, 1995\n| term_end3           = June 30, 2001\n| order4              = \n| term_start4         = August 15, 1987\n| term_end4           = June 30, 1992\n| order5              = [[President of the Senate of the Philippines#List of Senate Presidents|26th]]\n| office5             = President of the Senate of the Philippines\n| term_start5         = November 17, 2008\n| term_end5           = June 5, 2013\n| president5          = [[Gloria Macapagal Arroyo]]<br />[[Benigno Aquino III]]\n| predecessor5        = [[Manuel Villar|Manny Villar]]\n| successor5          = [[Franklin Drilon]]\n| order6              = \n| office6             = Member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]] from [[Cagayan]]'s [[Legislative districts of Cagayan#1st District|1st District]]\n| term_start6         = June 30, 1992\n| term_end6           = June 30, 1995\n| predecessor6        = Domingo A. Tuazon\n| successor6          = Patricio T. Antonio\n| office7             = [[Regular Batasang Pambansa|Mambabatas Pambansa (Assemblyman)]] from [[Cagayan]]\n| term_start7         = June 30, 1984\n| term_end7           = March 25, 1986<br />Served with:<br />Antonio C. Carag<br />Alfonso R. Reyno Jr.\n| office8             = [[Interim Batasang Pambansa|Mambabatas Pambansa (Assemblyman)]] from [[Cagayan Valley|Region II]]\n| term_start8         = June 12, 1978\n| term_end8           = June 5, 1984\n| order9              = \n| office9             = [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Minister of National Defense]]\n| term_start9         = January 4, 1972\n| term_end9           = November 23, 1986\n| president9          = [[Ferdinand Marcos]] <br /> [[Corazon Aquino]]\n| predecessor9        = Ferdinand Marcos\n| successor9          = [[Rafael Ileto]]\n| term_start10        = February 9, 1970\n| term_end10          = August 27, 1971\n| president10         = Ferdinand Marcos\n| predecessor10       = Ernesto Mata\n| successor10         = Ferdinand Marcos\n| order11             = \n| office11            = [[Department of Justice (Philippines)|Secretary of Justice]]\n| term_start11        = December 17, 1968\n| term_end11          = February 7, 1970\n| president11         = Ferdinand Marcos\n| predecessor11       = [[Claudio Teehankee|Claudio Teehankee Sr.]]\n| successor11         = Felix Makasiar\n| order12             = \n| office12            = [[Department of Finance (Philippines)|Secretary of Finance]] (''acting'')\n| term_start12        = 1966\n| term_end12          = 1968\n| president12         = Ferdinand Marcos\n| predecessor12       = Eduardo Romualdez\n| successor12         = Eduardo Romualdez\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1924|2|14}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Resume of Senator Enrile |url=http://www.senate.gov.ph/senators/sen_bio/enrile_resume.asp |website=Senate of the Philippines: 18th Congress |publisher=Senate of the Philippines |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n| birthplace         = [[Gonzaga, Cagayan|Gonzaga]], [[Cagayan]], [[Insular Government of the Philippine Islands|Philippine Islands]]\n| birth_name          = Juan Furagganan Ponce Enrile<ref>{{Philippine name|Furagganan|ph=natural}}</ref>\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = [[Filipino people|Filipino]]\n| party               = [[United Nationalist Alliance|UNA]] (2012\u2013present)\n| otherparty          = [[Nacionalista Party|Nacionalista]] (1965\u20131972; 1987\u20131995)<br />[[Kilusang Bagong Lipunan|KBL]] (1978\u20131986) <br /> [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal]] (1995\u20132001) <br /> [[Puwersa ng Masang Pilipino|PMP]] (2001\u20132012)\n| spouse              = Cristina Casta\u00f1er\n| relations           = \n| children            = [[Jack Enrile|Juan Ponce Enrile Jr.]]<br /> Katrina Ponce Enrile\n| residence           = [[Gonzaga, Cagayan]]<br />[[Dasmari\u00f1as Village]], [[Makati City]], [[Metro Manila]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Ateneo de Manila University]]<br />[[University of the Philippines College of Law]]<br />[[Harvard Law School]]\n| occupation          = [[Lawyer]]<br />Ponce Enrile, Reyes & Manalastas (1983\u20132020)\n| profession          = [[Politician]]\n| languages           = [[Ilocano language|Ilocano]], [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]], [[Ibanag language|Ibanag]], [[English language in the Philippines|English]]\n| religion            = [[Catholic Church in the Philippines|Roman Catholic]] <br /> <small> ''formerly'' [[Iglesia Filipina Independiente|Aglipayan]] </small>\n| signature           = \n| website             = \n| footnotes           = \n| caption             = Enrile in 2017\n}}\n\n'''Juan Furagganan Ponce Enrile Sr.''' ({{IPA-tl|hw\u0250\u031en \u02c8p\u0254\u031dns\u025b\u031d \u025bn\u02c8ril\u025b|lang}}; born February 14, 1924), abbreviated '''JPE''', is a [[Filipino people|Filipino]] [[politician]] and [[lawyer]]. He was a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[President of the Philippines|President]] [[Ferdinand Marcos]], and served as [[Department of Justice (Philippines)|Justice Secretary]] and [[Secretary of National Defense (Philippines)|Defense Minister]] under the [[History of the Philippines (1965-1986)|Marcos regime]]. He later became one of the leaders (along with General [[Fidel Ramos]]) of the [[People Power Revolution|1986 People Power Revolution]] that drove Marcos from power and into exile. Enrile has continued to be a prominent politician since then; he was [[Senate of the Philippines|Senate President]] from November 2008 until his resignation on June 5, 2013.\n\n==Early life and career==\nEnrile was born in [[Gonzaga, Cagayan]] to Petra Furagganan, the stepdaughter of a poor fisherman. He was born out of wedlock\u2014his Spanish ''mestizo'' father was the powerful regional politician and renowned lawyer Alfonso Ponce Enrile, who was already married. His second great-uncle was [[Mariano Ponce]]. As a young man, he was reunited with his father in the [[City of Manila]], and took his secondary education at [[St. James Academy (Malabon)|Saint James Academy]] in [[Malabon]].\n\nHe graduated [[Latin honors|''cum laude'']] in 1949 with an [[Associate of Arts]] degree from [[Ateneo de Manila University]]. Afterward, he attended the [[University of the Philippines]] [[University of the Philippines College of Law|College of Law]] and graduated ''cum laude'' with a [[Bachelor of Laws]] degree.  While in law school, he joined the Sigma Rho fraternity. Upon graduation, he was elected to the [[Pi Gamma Mu]] and [[Phi Kappa Phi]] international honor societies. He scored 11th in the 1953 [[Philippine Bar Examination|bar examinations]] with a 91.72% rating and a perfect score in mercantile law. As a scholar at the [[Harvard Law School]], he earned a [[Master of Laws]] degree with specialized training in international tax law.\n\nHe taught law at the [[Far Eastern University]] and practiced law in his father's law firm before taking responsibility for then Senator [[Ferdinand Marcos]]'s personal legal affairs in 1964, especially during the latter's term as Senate President.  After Marcos was elected president in 1965, Enrile became part of his inner circle. From 1966 to 1968, he was the Undersecretary and sometime Acting Secretary of the Department of Finance. He concurrently became acting Insurance Commissioner and Commissioner of the Bureau of Customs. From 1968 to 1970, he was the Secretary of Justice.\n\n==Career in the Marcos Cabinet==\n[[File:Marcos in Washington 1983.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Minister of National Defense Juan Ponce Enrile with President [[Ferdinand Marcos]].]]\n\nEnrile, like Marcos, comes from the northern Philippines, a region that had become Marcos' recruiting ground for key political and military leaders during his time. Enrile was with Marcos since his election in 1965.<ref name=\"ERF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1986/02/22/Enrile-and-Ramos-Former-loyalists-turn-on-Marcos/1656509432400/|title=Enrile and Ramos: Former loyalists turn on Marcos|publisher=}}</ref> His campaign efforts were rewarded with an appointment as chief of the Customs Bureau and the government's insurance commission.\n\nThe [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Department of National Defense]] would expand its power when Marcos assumed the presidency in 1965. Marcos appointed Enrile as his Secretary of National Defense on February 9, 1970, a position Enrile held until August 27, 1971, when he resigned to run unsuccessfully for the senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.ph/history-the-department-of-national-defense/|title=History: The Department of National Defense|publisher=}}</ref> He was re-appointed Defense Secretary by Marcos on January 4, 1972. As Defense Secretary, he was the highest ranked commissioned officer of a nation's armed forces.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\nFrom the beginning of Marcos' period in government, Enrile was one of the few that the former president trusted, and was seen by many as Marcos' prot\u00e9g\u00e9. For almost the entire period of [[Martial law in the Philippines|Martial Law]], Enrile served officially as the martial law administrator as he was in charge of all the armed forces' services during that time. Furthermore, as early as Marcos' planning and preparation for the declaration of martial law, Enrile was involved.<ref>[http://www.manilatimes.net/why-not-ask-ramos-and-enrile-about-martial-law-abuses/247486/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811031757/https://www.manilatimes.net/why-not-ask-ramos-and-enrile-about-martial-law-abuses/247486/ |date=August 11, 2018 }} Why Not Ask Ramos and Enrile About Martial Law Abuses</ref> In his memoir, Enrile recalls Marcos' careful preparations. He narrates that as early as December 1969, Marcos instructed him to study the 1935 Constitution, specifically the powers of the President as Commander-in-Chief. Marcos had already foreseen a rise in violence and chaos in the country and wanted to know the exact extent of his powers.<ref name=\"DML\" />\n                  \t\nAt the end of January of the following year, Enrile, with help from Efren Plana and Minerva Gonzaga Reyes, submitted the only copy of the report regarding the detailed nature and extent of Martial Law to Marcos. Soon after, Marcos allegedly ordered Enrile to prepare all documents necessary for the implementation of [[Martial Law in the Philippines]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16055240-juan-ponce-enrile | title=Juan Ponce Enrile, A Memoir | publisher=[[ABS-CBN Publishing]] | author=Juan Ponce Enrile | year=2012 | isbn=\n978-9-7181-6117-3 | editor=Navarro, Nelson A. }}</ref> In August 1972, Marcos once again met with Enrile and a few of his other most trusted commanders to discuss tentative dates for the declaration. By September 22, 1972, Marcos announced that he had placed the entire country under Martial Law as of 9 p.m. via proclamation 1081 which, he claimed, he had signed on September 21, 1972.<ref name=\"DML\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gov.ph/featured/declaration-of-martial-law/ | title=Declaration of Martial Law | work=[[Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines]] | accessdate= | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927014532/https://www.gov.ph/featured/declaration-of-martial-law/ | archivedate= September 27, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n[[File:Marcos Declares Martial Law.jpg|thumb|left|\"FM Declares Martial Law\"\u2014the headline of the September 24, 1972 issue of the ''Sunday Express'', which was the Sunday edition of the ''[[Philippines Daily Express]]''. The ''Daily Express'' was the only newspaper allowed to circulate upon the declaration of Martial Law.]]\n\nOne of Marcos' justifications for the declaration of martial law that year was terrorism. He cited the alleged ambush attack on Enrile's car on September 22, 1972 as pretext for martial law. At the time, many people doubted that the attack actually took place. Marcos, in his diary entry for September 1972, wrote that Enrile had been ambushed near Wack-Wack that night. He says \"it was a good thing he was riding in his security car as a protective measure\u2026 This makes the martial law proclamation a necessity.\"<ref name=\"DML\" /> On the contrary, Oscar Lopez, a resident of Wack-Wack who lived along the street of the alleged ambush, stated that he had heard a lot of shooting on the night of the incident. When he went out to see what was happening, he saw only an empty car riddled with bullets. Lopez' driver, who had happened to witness the incident, stated that \"there was a car that came and stopped beside a Meralco post. Some people exited the car, and another car came by to shoot at the car, to make it look like it was ambushed.\"<ref name=\"DML\" />\n\n[[File:Juan Ponce Enrile's Bullet-riddled car.jpg|thumb|left|Juan Ponce Enrile's bullet-riddled car]]\n \nThe doubts surrounding the alleged ambush were further confirmed in a press conference on February 23, 1986 when then Lieutenant General Fidel Ramos and Enrile admitted that the attack was staged in order to justify the declaration of martial law. Both radio and television media covered this and millions of Filipinos witnessed the said confession. Furthermore, in several interviews, Enrile was reported as indeed confirming that the attempted assassination was faked in order to justify the declaration of Martial Law.<ref name=\"ERF\" /><ref name=\"Inquirer\" >{{cite web | url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/284836/true-or-false-was-1972-enrile-ambush-faked#ixzz4QFSz3iDu | title=True or false: Was 1972 Enrile ambush faked? | work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] | date=October 8, 2012 | accessdate=December 23, 2019 | author=Inquirer Research}}</ref> Conflicting accounts arise in his book, ''Juan Ponce Enrile: A Memoir''. In the said book, Enrile accuses his political opponents of spreading rumors of the ambush being staged despite having already admitted several times that the attempted assassination was indeed fake.<ref name=\"Memoir review\">{{cite web | url=https://book2luv.blogspot.com/2018/03/juan-ponce-enrile-memoir_25.html | title=Juan Ponce Enrile, A Memoir | work=The Book Lover blog | date=March 25, 2018 | accessdate=December 19, 2019 | author=Aenlle, Mike }}</ref><ref name=\"Inquirer\" />\n\nDespite later controversy, at the time, Enrile remained one of Marcos' most loyal allies. In 1973, under the new modified [[parliamentary system]] then in place under the country's new constitution under Martial Law, Enrile's title became Defense Minister. Enrile focused his efforts on a broad review of defense policies and on dealing with pressing social unrest. The abolition of civilian institutions such as [[Congress of the Philippines|Congress]], the weakening of the judiciary, and the outlawing of [[Political party|political parties]], left the military as the only other instrumentality of the national government outside of the Presidency.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\nAccording to the [[National Historical Institute of the Philippines]], Enrile was also appointed as the general for logging in the Philippines. He was tasked by Marcos to give certificates to logging companies, which eventually led to one of Asia's most devastating environmental disasters. During that time, the forest cover of the Philippines shrank until only 8% remained. Enrile also owned numerous logging companies such as Ameco in Bukidnon, Dolores Timber in Samar, San Jose Timber in Northern Samar, Kasilagan Softwood Development Corp in Butuan, Eurasia Match in Cebu, Pan Oriental which operates in Cebu and Butuan, Palawan-Apitong Corp in Palawan, and Royal Match. He also invested heavily in a rubber plantation in Basilan. A share of the Marcos ill-gotten wealth was siphoned in those companies. Enrile was also appointed by Marcos as the President of the [[Philippine Coconut Authority]], where he established control of the copra industry together with Danding Cojuangco. The two ruled over the controversial Coco Levy Fund which proved their intense corruption in government service. The fund, which was supposed to be used to improve the country's copra industry, was used by the two for programs led by Imelda Marcos and other [[Marcos cronies]]. A huge portion of the fund was also used for the presidential campaigns of Ferdinand Marcos in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5reVY2X8PS0|title=EP09 KAYO ANG HIHIRAP KAMI ANG YAYAMAN|publisher=[[National Historical Commission of the Philippines]]|date=September 20, 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nOn November 28, 1978, Marcos issued the Letter of Instruction no. 776, which stated that \"No changes of assignment of senior officers including provincial commanders, brigade commanders, division commanders, and special unit commanders shall be made without clearance from the president.\"<ref>[http://www.gov.ph/1978/11/28/letter-of-instruction-no-776-s-1978/] Letter of Instruction No. 776</ref> By the 1980s, Marcos began to bypass Enrile's authority. He clipped the powers of the Minister of National Defense and the Chief of Staff over the Armed Forces of the Philippines.<ref name=\"Seesaw Life\">{{cite web | url=http://www.philstar.com/opinion/2015/09/09/1497632/seesaw-life-juan-ponce-enrile | title=The Seesaw Life of Juan Ponce Enrile | work=[[The Philippine Star]] | date=September 8, 2015 | accessdate=December 23, 2019 | author=Katigbak, Tony }}</ref>\n\nAfter opposition leader Senator [[Benigno Aquino, Jr.|Benigno \"Ninoy\" Aquino, Jr.]] was [[Assassination of Benigno Aquino, Jr.|assassinated on August 21, 1983]], Enrile started to break away from the increasingly unpopular Marcos dictatorship. He began aligning himself with dissident elements in the army, particularly the [[Reform the Armed Forces Movement]] - which was then headed by his [[Aide-de-camp]], Lieutenant Colonel Gregorio Honasan. On February 15, 1986, Aquino's wife, [[Cory Aquino]], gained mass support through her oath taking in protest of Marcos being announced president. This then led to many leaders joining the revolution and fight against Marcos.<ref name=\"Tavaana\"/>\n\nOfficers from the group, with Enrile's support, launched a ''[[coup d'\u00e9tat]]'' against Marcos in February 1986. Marcos was alerted to the plot by Ver, and the conspirators took refuge in two military camps. From there, Enrile and then Lieutenant General [[Fidel Ramos]], the head of the defunct [[Philippine Constabulary]] (it had been integrated with the INP to form the [[Philippine National Police]]) and concurrently vice-chief of staff of the armed forces, rallied opponents against Marcos in a citizens' revolt that became known as the [[People Power Revolution]]. They called on the people to gather in Epifanio de los Santos Avenue ([[EDSA (road)|EDSA]]) to support on February 22. The next three days, they continued their rally in EDSA now containing two million people in support. The growing number encouraged many more leaders to support the movement against Marcos. Enrile stated, \"It was funny.\u2026 We in the defense and military organizations who should be protecting the people were being protected by them.\"<ref name=\"Tavaana\">{{cite web | url=https://tavaana.org/en/en/content/people-power-revolution-philippines-i-saw-no-one-yield-fear | title=People Power Revolution Philippines: I Saw No One Yield | publisher=Tavaana | accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career in the Aquino Cabinet==\nEnrile then served as the Secretary of National Defense under Corazon Aquino, who had replaced Marcos as president, but he increasingly differed with Aquino, specifically on the administration's handling of insurgent leftist opposition. Aquino sought to make peace with the communist party of the Philippines through the use and promotions of ceasefires during which peace talks were to be held between the government and the leftist opposition. Because of such tactics, Enrile was not the only person dissatisfied with Aquino administration. Many of the younger officers in the military who had been identified as members of the Reform the Armed Forces Movement and Marcos loyalists sought to oust Aquino from the presidency with the many coups that were plotted from 1986 to 1990. The earliest and most prominent one was the [[1986-1990 Philippine coup attempts|\"God Save the Queen\" plot]] that was to supposedly be executed on the November 11, 1986.<ref>[http://www.gov.ph/1990/10/03/the-final-report-of-the-fact-finding-commission-ii-political-change-and-military-transmition-in-the-philippines-1966-1989-from-the-barracks-to-the-corridors-of-power/] Final Report of the Fact Finding Commission</ref> The investigation of the coup done by the Fact Finding Commission found that Enrile and some members of the RAM as the primary instigators of the coup. After revealing the fruits of the investigation findings, Aquino forced Enrile to resign as Defense Secretary in November 1986 as she had lost confidence in him. Enrile was then replaced with [[Rafael Ileto]].\n\n==Congressional career==\n\n===First Senate term===\nIn May 1987 Enrile won a seat in the [[1987 Philippine Senate election|1987 election]] as one of two opposition members in the country's 24-member [[Senate of the Philippines|Senate]] (the other being [[Joseph Estrada]]), finishing 24th. He was unable to be proclaimed until August, when the electoral protest filed by Augusto Sanchez was dismissed. He formally assumed office on August 15, 1987. In the same month, an [[1986\u20131987 Philippine coup attempts|attempted coup against Aquino]] escalated and led to the destruction of the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines|Armed Forces]] General Headquarters (AFPGHQ) in [[Camp Aguinaldo]] in [[Quezon City]]. He was detained in Camp Aguinaldo over suspicion of planning the coup with Lt. Col. [[Gregorio Honasan]], but was released days later for lack of evidence. Enrile later stated numerous recalls about the martial law era, of which all were flip-flops from his previous statements during his term a secretary of defense and during the ouster of Marcos. He was dubbed by then-President [[Corazon Aquino]] as \"''Pambansang Balimbing''\" (national political turncoat) for his contradicting statements and \"''Dakilang Miron''\" (great bystander) for his inconvenient bystander and opportunistic attitude.<ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6d8JJzuks0Q&t=13s|title=President Corazon Aquino blasts Enrile and coup rebels at EDSA (1990)|first=|last=Maypagasa|date=August 23, 2015|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref name=\"youtube.com\"/>\n\n===Member of the House of Representatives===\nIn 1992, before his term in the Senate had ended, Enrile predicted that he might lose the senatorial election or win, but only serve three years in office. Under the transitory provisions of the [[Philippine Constitution|1987 Constitution]], the 12 candidates who receive the greatest number of votes serve a six-year term, the next 12 only three years. He ran instead for the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines]]. He [[1992 Philippine House of Representatives elections|was elected]] and represented the First District of [[Cagayan]].\n\n===Second to fourth senate terms===\nIn 1995 Enrile ran in the senatorial race as an independent candidate for [[Senate of the Philippines|senator]] and was also a guest candidate under the [[Lakas NUCD|Lakas]]&ndash;[[Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino|Laban]] coalition. He [[1995 Philippine Senate election|won as senator]] and held the position until 2001. During his term as senator, he ran as an independent candidate in the [[1998 Philippine presidential election|1998 election]] for the position of [[President of the Philippines|President]]. He lost to then [[Vice President of the Philippines|Vice President]] Joseph Estrada.\n\nOn January 13, 2001 he was one of those who voted against the opening of the second bank envelope.{{clarify|date=September 2011}} That vote led to the [[EDSA II|second EDSA People Power Revolution]] that eventually ousted President Estrada. From April 30 to May 1, 2001, together with [[Miriam Defensor Santiago]], [[Gregorio Honasan]], [[Panfilo Lacson]] and [[Vicente Sotto III]], he led the [[EDSA III]] protests in support of [[Joseph Estrada]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/90521/miriam-gma-resign-or-we-will-storm-palace|title= Miriam to GMA: Resign or we will storm palace\n|newspaper=[[Philippine Star]]|date=April 30, 2001|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"EDSA INC\" />  May 1, 2001, the protesters stormed [[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace]].<ref name=\"EDSA INC\" >{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/in-depth/104045-edsa-3-iglesia-ni-cristo|title= Remembering the Iglesia-led EDSA 3\n|work=[[Rappler]]|date=August 25, 2015|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref> In May 2001 he was indicted by the military for the investigation of the unsuccessful siege of the [[Malaca\u00f1an Palace]] by pro-Estrada forces. He was released a day later. He ran for [[2001 Philippine Senate election|reelection]] as part of the [[Puwersa ng Masa]] coalition. Due to the issues that haunted him over the failed siege, he lost the election.\n\nIn the [[2004 Philippine Senate election|2004 election]], he made a comeback bid for the Senate under the [[Koalisyon ng Nagkakaisang Pilipino]] (KNP) banner. He actively opposed the imposition of the Purchased Power Adjustment (PPA) on consumers' electric bills. Due to his expos\u00e9 of the PPA and the [[Supreme Court of the Philippines|Supreme Court]] decision in favour of a refund on electric bills, the public responded positively and elected him. He thus became a senator in three non-consecutive terms. He was reelected as senator in the [[2010 Philippine Senate election|2010 election]]s. {{asof|2013}}, he is the oldest senator of the [[15th Congress of the Philippines]]. Enrile is affiliated with the [[Pwersa ng Masang Pilipino]] (PMP). Technically he belongs to an opposition party, but in the Senate, he stands as an independent and is part of the administration bloc. The minority bloc includes all of his party's members.\n\n==Senate Presidency==\n\n===Election===\nOn November 17, 2008, Senate President [[Manuel Villar]] resigned due to lack of support, and Enrile succeeded him the same day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.easybourse.com/bourse-actualite/marches/senators-name-juan-ponce-enrile-as-new-philippine-senate-562997|title=easybourse.com, Senators Name Juan Ponce Enrile As New Philippine Senate President|access-date=November 17, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221140806/http://www.easybourse.com/bourse-actualite/marches/senators-name-juan-ponce-enrile-as-new-philippine-senate-562997|archive-date=December 21, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=ABS>{{cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/11/17/08/enrile-ousts-villar-senate-coup|title=(Update) Enrile ousts Villar in Senate coup|first=ABS-CBN|last=News|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-11/17/content_10371979.htm news.xinhuanet.com, Philippine senate president resigns] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221153448/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-11/17/content_10371979.htm |date=December 21, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/133995/Zubiri-is-new-Senate-Majority-Leader|title=Zubiri is new Senate Majority Leader|publisher=}}</ref> Enrile was nominated by [[Panfilo Lacson]]; 14 senators supported the nomination and five abstained.<ref name=ABS/> Enrile accepted the position, saying that \"To lead the Senate with its great minds, strong advocacies, varying and independent political beliefs and leanings, is not an easy task. But it is precisely this variance in points of view and the battle of great ideas that provide the dynamism we need to craft legislation that takes into account and balances the competing interests involved \u2013 with the end in view of serving the greater good of the people to whom we owe our mandate.\"{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n\n===Legislation===\nUnder his leadership, the Senate passed vital pieces of legislation such as the CARP Extension, Anti-Torture Act, Expanded Senior Citizens Act, Anti-Child Pornography Act, National Heritage Conservation Act, Real Estate Investment Act, among many others. Institutional reforms were also implemented within the Senate to improve the daily conduct of business as well the welfare of its officers and employees.\n\n===Maguindanao martial law===\nThe Senate also collaborated with the House of Representatives on two crucial issues which are now considered historical milestones. In December 2009, it used Proclamation No. 1959 of the previous administration, declaring a state of martial law and suspending the privilege of the writ of ''[[habeas corpus]]'' in the province of Maguindanao, while in May 2010, Congress convened to constitute itself as the national board to canvass the votes for president and vice president, and proclaim the winners.\n\n===Re-election as Senate President===\n[[File:Hajime Ishii and Juan Ponce Enrile 20110504.jpg|thumb|200px|with [[Hajime Ishii]] (left) on May 4, 2011]]\n\nEnrile was re-elected to a fourth term in the [[2010 Philippine Senate election|2010 Senate election]]. On July 26, 2010, he was re-elected President of the Senate. Enrile committed himself to \"discharge my duties and responsibilities with honor, with total devotion to our institution, and with fairness to all members. No partisan consideration will blur or color the treatment of any member of the Senate. We are all Senators elected by the people to serve them with dedication to their interest and well-being and devotion to our responsibilities.\" Furthermore, in his acceptance speech, he enjoined his colleagues to \"uphold the independence and integrity of this Senate, without abandoning our duty to cooperate with the other departments of the government to achieve what is good for our people.\"<ref>[https://www.senate.gov.ph/senators/senpres/enrile.asp] Biography of Senate Presidents - Juan Ponce Enrile. Retrieved November 29, 2016</ref>\n\n===Corona's impeachment, various feuds, and controversies===\nIn early 2012 Enrile was the presiding officer of the [[Impeachment of Renato Corona|Impeachment of Chief Justice Renato Corona]]. He was one of the 20 Senators voting guilty for the impeachment. In September 2012 he started a feud with [[Antonio Trillanes IV]] when he asked Trillanes why he secretly visited [[Beijing]] to talk about the [[Philippines and the Spratly Islands]] dispute on [[Spratlys]] and the [[Scarborough Shoal]]. Trillanes said his visit in China was authorized by the [[Malaca\u00f1an|Palace]]. He also alleged that Enrile was being pushed by former Pres. [[Gloria Arroyo]] to pass a bill splitting the province of [[Camarines Sur]] into two but Enrile denied the allegation.\n\nIn late 2012, Enrile also started a feud with [[Miriam Defensor Santiago]] when Santiago authored the [[Responsible Parenthood and Reproductive Health Act of 2012]] with [[Pia Cayetano]], which he opposed. In January 2013, Santiago exposed that Enrile allegedly gave PhP 1.6 million each to his fellow Senators, except for her, [[Pia Cayetano]], [[Alan Peter Cayetano]], and Trillanes, who were reportedly to have been only given PhP 250 thousand each. He admitted giving the said amount to the senators, saying it was part of the balance of the maintenance and other operating expenses (MOOE) funds allowed per senator. On January 21, 2013, because of the controversies involving him, he attempted to vacate his position as Senate President but his motion was rejected.\n\n===Resignation===\nAmid accusations against him, including the alleged distribution of MOOE funds to senators, Enrile stepped down as Senate President after his privilege speech on June 5, 2013.<ref>[http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/311510/news/nation/enrile-resigns-as-senate-president Enrile resigns as Senate president] retrieved June 5, 2013</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n\n===Enrile cash gift===\nIn January 2013, while sitting as the Senate President, Enrile was accused of using Senate funds called MOOE as Christmas gifts to members of the senate who do not oppose him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/19395-enrile-s-cash-gifts-exclude-4-critics|title=Enrile's 'cash gifts' exclude 4 critics|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/337461/enrile-gave-18-senators-p1-6m-each-for-christmas|title=Enrile gave 18 senators P1.6M each for Christmas|first=Juliet|last=Labog-Javellana|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/289408/news/nation/enrile-gave-p1-6m-to-all-fellow-senators-except-his-foes|title=Enrile gave P1.6M to all fellow senators except his foes|publisher=}}</ref> This led to his resignation as Senate President without sufficiently answering the controversy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/421361/enrile-quits-slams-critics|title=Enrile quits, slams critics|first=Cathy|last=Yamsuan|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Pork barrel scam===\n{{main|Priority Development Assistance Fund scam}}\n[[File:Bong Revilla after delivering \"Salamat, Kaibigan\".jpg|thumb|200px|Enrile with Senators [[Jinggoy Estrada]] (left) and [[Bong Revilla]] (center) after Revilla's Privilege Speech at the Senate floor on June 9, 2014]]\n\nIn September 2013, Enrile was again involved in misappropriated funds, this time with regard to the PDAF or what is commonly called the [[pork barrel]] fund. Twenty billion pesos worth of Priority Development Fund was illegally channeled through various bogus NGOs of Janet Napoles which most of it being used by the Senator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2013/09/14/1208471/luy-napoles-ngos-shifted-pork-lgus-2011|title=Luy: Napoles NGOs shifted \u2018pork\u2019 to LGUs in 2011 - Philstar.com|website=philstar.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/473291/chief-aide-in-charge-of-enriles-pdaf-deals|title=Chief aide in charge of Enrile\u2019s PDAF deals|first=Gil C.|last=Cabacungan|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nEnrile, along with fellow senators [[Bong Revilla]], and [[Jinggoy Estrada]], were indicted for [[plunder]] and for the violation of the Anti-Graft and Corrupt Practices Act before the Sandiganbayan  on June 6, 2014 in connection to the [[Priority Development Assistance Fund scam]]. Alleged mastermind Janet Lim Napoles and Enrile's former chief of staff Gigi Reyes were also charged. Enrile allegedly received \u20b1172 million in kickbacks from public funds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/59826-enrile-jpe-jinggoy-charged-plunder-pdaf-scam|title=3 PH senators charged with plunder over PDAF scam|publisher=}}</ref> He was detained on July 3, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/617113/enrile-in-hospital-arrest-gigi-reyes-at-qc-jail|title=Enrile in hospital arrest; Gigi Reyes at QC jail|first=Dona Z. Pazzibugan, TJ|last=Burgonio|publisher=}}</ref> and suspended from his Senate post<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/634331/senate-carries-out-enrile-suspension|title=Senate carries out Enrile suspension|first=Maila|last=Ager|publisher=}}</ref> on September 1, 2014 for these charges, after his motions to post bail to lift the suspension order were denied.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mb.com.ph/enriles-motion-to-fix-bail-denied |title=Archived copy |access-date=September 3, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905014344/http://www.mb.com.ph/enriles-motion-to-fix-bail-denied/ |archive-date=September 5, 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/08/22/14/sandigan-denies-enriles-plea-not-be-suspended|title=Sandigan denies Enrile's plea not to be suspended|first=ABS-CBN|last=News|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nEnrile, or \"''Manong Johnny''\" as he is often called (''manong'' is an [[Ilokano language|Ilocano]] term of endearment for an older brother), is married to Cristina Casta\u00f1er, a Spaniard, who has served as the Philippine Ambassador to the [[Holy See]]. They have two children: Juan Jr. (Jack) and Katrina. Juan Jr. is currently congressman for the 1st District of [[Cagayan]] and running for a Senate seat under [[United Nationalist Alliance|UNA]], while Katrina is currently CEO of Enrile's company Jaka Group, which owns the Philippine Match Company. Enrile has a half-sister, [[Armida Siguion-Reyna]], who is a singer as well as a theatre and film actress.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Flores|first1=Wilson Lee|title=Armida Siguion-Reyna: The singer, the song, her fight for artistic freedom, her love for Imelda & Kris|url=http://www.philstar.com/sunday-life/2015/02/22/1426174/armida-siguion-reyna-singer-song-her-fight-artistic-freedom-her-love|work=The Philippine Star|date=February 22, 2015|quote=She is also known as the half-sister of former Senate President Juan Ponce Enrile.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ca\u00f1ares-Yamsuan|first1=Cathy|title='Aawitan Kita': In biography, Armida Siguion-Reyna faces the music|url=http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/185284/aawitan-kita-in-biography-armida-siguion-reyna-faces-the-music/|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=February 23, 2015|quote=Navarro, who also edited the self-titled autobiography of Armida's elder brother Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile released in 2012, recalled that Estrada summoned top movie producers for dinner in Malaca\u00f1ang on July 9, 1999.}}</ref>\n\nEnrile's rumored affair with his former long-time employee and chief of staff Jessica Lucila \"Gigi\" Reyes, 38 years his junior, came out after reports that Enrile's wife, Cristina, walked out on him in January 1998 after charging him with adultery. The news made both local and international headlines.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schmetzer|first1=Uli|title=Filipinos Riveted By Their Own News Of High-level Trysts|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-01-30/news/9801300110_1_filipinos-sen-juan-ponce-enrile-president-fidel-ramos|work=Chicago Tribune|date=January 30, 1998}}</ref> Gigi Reyes was regarded as \"the door, if not the bridge\" to Enrile, referring to the extent of closeness between the two. Enrile's special fondness for Reyes was again called out by Sen. [[Alan Peter Cayetano]], after Reyes accused Cayetano in a media interview of hypocrisy for supposedly receiving a \"cash gift\" from Enrile.<ref name=\"rappler.com\">{{cite news|last1=Hofile\u00f1a|first1=Chay|title='The Boss' and Gigi Reyes|url=http://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/40261-boss-enrile-gigi-reyes|work=Rappler|date=October 1, 2013}}</ref> The incident led to Reyes's resignation from Enrile's office, which Reyes said was also for her criticising on how Enrile responded to the issue of fund misuse. Enrile insisted the resignation was because of rumors of their illicit relationship.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Macaraig|first1=Ayee|title=Gigi Reyes packs up from Enrile office|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/20611-gigi-reyes-packs-up-from-enrile-office|work=Rappler|date=January 28, 2013}}</ref> Reyes's name was once again linked to Enrile's name for signing documents that facilitated the release of Enrile's PDAF to fake non-governmental organizations (NGOs) linked to Janet Lim Napoles, the woman who is said to be behind the PDAF scam.<ref name=\"rappler.com\"/>\n\n==Seeking clemency for those convicted of the Aquino assassination==\nOn August 21, 2007, the 24th anniversary of Senator Aquino's death, Enrile stated that the case of the 14 soldiers incarcerated for 24 years for his assassination should be reviewed for clemency. Enrile paid for the legal services of the soldiers during their trial, and said the soldiers and their families had suffered enough. Fifteen soldiers of the Aviation Security Command had been sentenced to double life imprisonment for the double murder of Aquino and his alleged lone communist gunman, [[Rolando Galman]], and one of them had since died. They were all acquitted in December 1985 by the [[Sandiganbayan]]'s Manuel Pamaran, but when the entire proceedings were invalidated by the Supreme Court and the case retried, the Sandiganbayan's Regino C. Hermosisima, Jr. (promoted as [[Supreme Court of the Philippines|Supreme Court Associate Justice]]) convicted them again on September 28, 1990.<ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view_article.php?article_id=83821  Inquirer.net, Enrile seeks clemency for soldiers in Aquino slay] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013123302/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view_article.php?article_id=83821 |date=October 13, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*Portrayed by [[Joonee Gamboa]] in the 1988 TV drama film ''[[A Dangerous Life]]''\n\n*Portrayed by [[Enrique Gil]] in the TV drama anthology series ''[[Maalaala Mo Kaya]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jpenrile.com]\n*[http://www.senate.gov.ph/senators/sen_bio/enrile_bio.asp]\n*[http://www.i-site.ph/Databases/Congress/13thSenate/SALS/enrile-SAL.html Juan Ponce Enrile's Assets and Liabilities]\n*[http://www.senate.gov.ph/senators/sen_bio/enrile_bio.asp  Juan Ponce Enrile's Official Philippine Senate biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box |\n  before= [[Manny Villar]] |\n  title= [[President of the Senate of the Philippines]]&nbsp;|\n  years= November 17, 2008 \u2013 June 5, 2013 |\n  after= [[Jinggoy Estrada]]\n}}\n{{succession box |\n  before= Ernesto Mata <br /> [[Ferdinand Marcos]] |\n  title= [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Philippine Secretary of National 